2992, -0.012079043, 0.010163384, -0.02758569, 0.009987118, 0.0042265314, 0.026650773, 0.04634866, 0.016487278, 0.031014366, 0.008725649, -0.04769757, 0.015104327, 0.024921637, -0.02019325, 6.938087E-4, 0.07633614, 0.08482923, -0.022121014, 0.0136428755, -0.02820574, 0.021671051, 0.008001194, -0.051782202, -0.02454998, -0.043836325, -0.013392424], text:"Review\nLRRK2 in Parkinson's disease: upstream\nregulation and therapeutic targeting\nYulan Xiong\n1,* and Jianzhong Yu2\nMutations in leucine-rich repeat kinase 2 (LRRK2) are the most common causes of\nParkinson's disease (PD) to date. Dysfunction in LRRK2 enzymatic activities and\nelevated protein levels are associated with the disease. How is LRRK2 activated,\nand what downstream molecular and cellular processes does LRRK2 regulate?\nAddressing these questions is crucial to decipher the disease mechanisms. In\nthis review we focus on the upstream regulations and brieﬂy discuss downstream\nsubstrates of LRRK2 as well as the cellular consequences caused by these regula-\ntions. Building on these basic ﬁndings, we discuss therapeutic strategies targeting\nLRRK2 and highlight the challenges in clinical trials. We further highlight the impor-\ntant questions that remains to be answered in the LRRK2 ﬁeld.\nLRRK2: the most common genetic cause of Parkinson's disease\nMutations in the LRRK2 gene, corresponding to the PARK8 locus, were discovered to be associ-\nated with Parkinson's disease (PD) in 2004, two decades ago [1,2]. Since then a variety of\nmutations in LRRK2 have been rapidly identiﬁed and found to be the most common causes of\nboth sporadic and familial PD (see Glossary), accounting for 1–2% of all cases of PD. Clinically,\nLRRK2-mediated disease is nearly indistinguishable from sporadic PD [3]. Given its strong genetic\nlink to PD, LRRK2 represents a clear and compelling target for therapeutic development in PD. In\nthe past 20 years its basic function, disease mechanisms, and therapeutic potential have been ex-\ntensively investigated, leading to signiﬁcant advances. However, the precise function of LRRK2 and\nhow it is activated remain unclear. It is unknown why LRRK2 affects dopaminergic (DA) neurons in\nthe substantia nigra pars compacta (SNpc) in particular, and whether targeting LRRK2 would slow", page:1}}, {_id:2511, properties:{chunk_index:1, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p1::1::e63a433e", embedding:[0.026609616, 0.054055285, -0.13810307, -0.018864771, 0.031371064, -0.02912846, 0.055673238, 0.04088289, -0.0050232667, -0.046932086, -0.016526442, 0.09086135, 0.0919266, -0.0031359233, 0.01903011, -0.027999673, -0.0048849173, 0.010038127, -0.0027768132, 0.028881924, -0.055429995, -0.0053926967, 0.016647508, -0.022388235, 0.06449074, 0.06597111, 0.019420652, -0.06362524, 0.04429824, 0.026753135, 0.08706816, -0.028326409, -0.004406051, -0.03416826, -0.0051018787, -0.040840484, 0.05819377, 0.03350097, -0.02043415, 0.064341135, -0.025604758, -0.02677317, -0.021295346, -0.08469505, -0.0097638285, 0.04397311, 0.020326039, 0.0118177915, 0.071375586, -0.068228774, 0.029492967, 0.007922576, -0.010849369, -0.045356125, 0.10551675, 0.021032706, -0.015600932, 0.0102305, -0.004712426, -0.0066695106, 0.06036482, 0.059721693, -0.05386332, 0.020553619, 0.04528461, -0.07192847, -0.023619147, 0.019663963, -0.0066164397, -0.032251935, 0.02303839, 0.0124817155, -0.018519057, 0.026580753, 0.005817209, -0.0013227224, 0.030058436, -0.011340274, -0.03402383, -0.0387065, 0.001976448, -0.018597597, 0.053868376, 0.0068971296, 0.050978843, 0.027758697, -0.047325786, 0.002154177, -0.028879734, 0.04343066, 0.03746015, 0.01670755, 0.04298537, 8.065651E-4, -0.06777016, 0.032812268, 0.055542503, -2.260284E-4, -0.025038017, 0.00780402, -0.011200701, 0.005832071, 0.06179874, 0.008004245, 0.039261382, 0.056281485, 0.06125922, -0.004682619, 0.00864237, 0.004659611, -0.047848195, 0.0401863, 0.0065284325, -0.03277455, 0.0017132838, 0.029843481, 0.01948088, -0.0077551533, 0.0041145487, 0.040539548, -0.0352