70915623, 0.053592227, 0.033778567, -0.011705717, -0.067106746, 0.011641139, -0.0054805796, -0.030499212, 0.06346514, -0.0045704483, 0.029983433, 0.012244673, -0.03247831, -0.02215394, 0.014899709, -0.037736543, -0.0121531915, 0.021414628, -0.038238764, -0.02705734, -0.02783383, -0.030224381, -0.04489097, -0.0041860384, 0.0010908084, 0.010810133, -0.024034929, 0.030388664, 0.0029327285, 0.046936493, 0.03587864, 0.046562463, 0.023634937, -0.007811875, -0.030243395, 0.025500229, -0.0134148495, -0.0044730403, -0.013001044, 0.079295166, 0.11208693, -0.03942817, 0.037463386, -0.040781118, 0.051835548, 0.0022235399, -0.054048754, 0.0040489943, -0.027338497, -0.026583022], text:"how it is activated remain unclear. It is unknown why LRRK2 affects dopaminergic (DA) neurons in\nthe substantia nigra pars compacta (SNpc) in particular, and whether targeting LRRK2 would slow\ndown the progression of PD. In this review we discuss current progress in understanding the mo-\nlecular mechanisms of LRRK2, with a focus on its upstream regulation and how it becomes acti-\nvated, and provide a brief discussion on downstream substrates and cellular consequences. We\nfurther discuss therapeutic strategies and challenges in targeting LRRK2.\nLRRK2 genetic variants in PD\nWith respect to the degree of the association with the disease, three categories of genetic variants\nof LRRK2 can be assigned. First, the mutations in the coding region of LRRK2 that segregate with\nthe disease in large families are considered to be pathogenic (causative) and have the strongest\neffects on the disease phenotype. Second, non-coding variants at the LRRK2 locus identiﬁed by\ngenome-wide association studies (GWAS), contribute to the risk of PD, but have modest effects.\nThird, several LRRK2 variants have been detected in PD cases but appear to have no effects on\nPD susceptibility. We focus on discussing the ﬁrst two categories, which involve changes in\nLRRK2 amino acids (the coding variants) or affect LRRK2 expression levels (noncoding variants).\nAmino acid variants – changes in enzymatic function\nLRRK2 is a unique and large multifunctional protein that contains two important enzymatic\ndomains deﬁned as a GTPase domain consisting of a RAS of complex (ROC) domain together\nHighlights\nMutations in LRRK2 are the most com-\nmon causes of Parkinson's disease\n(PD). Dysfunction in LRRK2 enzymatic\nactivities and elevated protein levels are\nassociated with the disease.\nHigher-order dimerization/oligomeriza-\ntion and membrane recruitment appear\nto be required for LRRK2 activation.\nRab29/12/38/32/8/10 and VPS35 are\nemerging upstream activators of LRRK2.\nA unique feature of LRRK2 is that it pos-", page:1}}, {_id:2512, properties:{chunk_index:2, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p1::2::9c6f638d", embedding:[-0.04185113, 0.06995431, -0.13871138, 0.02162037, 0.088812456, -0.0872257, 0.057492647, 0.042260587, 0.018944096, -0.031230073, -0.02660116, 0.08502336, 0.08458951, -0.006314823, 0.025830518, -0.05675365, 8.54219E-4, -0.00943713, -3.1576623E-4, 0.0669297, -0.06278961, -0.009678615, 0.029792005, -0.040248383, 0.07527698, 0.05042265, 0.04378188, -0.04305897, -0.034878768, 0.01606602, 0.051803857, -0.07328593, -0.029939389, -0.020033555, -0.05084841, -0.043247875, 0.09399141, 0.0127068255, -0.021408407, -0.013117597, -0.009113744, 0.023163762, 0.029870695, -0.03575387, -0.018529356, -0.0059504327, -0.02074579, -0.006034549, 0.06274035, -0.06156518, 0.018320713, 0.036436863, -0.019556487, -0.027737098, 0.112311505, 0.013019662, -0.010794418, -0.0147095295, 0.0075435084, 0.015017104, 0.07176178, 0.08841819, -0.021882035, 0.014564054, 0.072025314, -0.040670283, 1.9615158E-4, 0.019571755, -0.029984072, -0.06301399, 0.010537682, -0.04242867, -0.0029175512, 5.151495E-5, 0.003647555, -0.028433617, 0.006333651, -0.02263493, 0.0058530783, 0.01632731, 0.02686049, -0.039923, 0.08001549, 0.011861238, 0.053140715, 0.013480581, -0.0841818, -0.005253898, -0.024754936, 0.05530393, 0.01669