4513522, 0.010160633, -0.0638188, -0.08888128, -0.0018797029, -0.02209404, -0.01267341, 0.06168244, -0.03033937, 0.011699101, 0.010184256, -0.010669989, -0.018512098, -0.039738007, 0.004194556, -0.023033848, 0.024689062, -0.05699069, 0.014550662, -0.056496292, -0.062494688, -0.027714072, 0.0017702602, 0.024832401, 0.03354494, -0.014659978, 0.024173943, -0.01309647, 0.04641007, 0.045623973, 0.05331797, 0.0148460455, 8.5534196E-4, -0.02180027, 0.04016587, -0.007210041, 0.025503296, -0.011579344, 0.060296927, 0.05711218, 0.008692755, 0.027334468, -0.044321716, 0.022032559, -0.007983164, -0.025992528, 0.0064678546, -0.03391578, -0.042617217], text:"with a C-terminal of ROC (COR) domain, and also contains a kinase domain and multiple protein–\nprotein interacting domains [4] (Figure 1). Although hundreds of mutations have been suggested\nto modify disease risk, eight mutations (N1437H, R1441C/G/H/S, Y1699C, G2019S, and\nI2020T) [5] are conﬁrmed to segregate with the disease in large families (Figure 1). Regarding their\nrespective effects on LRRK2 enzymatic activities, the mutations in the kinase domain (G2019S\nand I2020T) increase LRRK2 kinase activity, whereas the mutations in the ROC domain (R1441C/\nG) and in the COR domain (Y1699C) diminish LRRK2 GTPase activity. Interestingly, these mutations\n(R1441C/G and Y1699C) also enhance LRRK2 kinase activity, probably indirectly, to an even\ngreater extent than those in the kinase domain [6,7]. LRRK2 variants R1628P and G2385R are\nassociated with increased PD risk in Asian populations [1,8]. Disease-linked mutations in LRRK2\nhave also been identiﬁed in Crohn's disease, leprosy, and tuberculosis, suggesting that LRRK2\nalso functions in the periphery [9–11]. Because PD-causing mutations are predominantly found in\nenzymatic domains, indicating that LRRK2 enzymatic activity plays a crucial role in PD pathogenesis,\nextensive work has focused on LRRK2 enzymatic functions, speciﬁcally the kinase function, and\ntremendous efforts have been put into the development of LRRK2 kinase inhibitors.\nNoncoding variants – changes in expression level\nIn 2009, GWAS analysis identiﬁed common genetic variants at or near the LRRK2 locus, for exam-\nple the LRRK2 promoter variant rs76904798, as risk factors for PD [12,13], suggesting that LRRK2\ncan contribute to PD pathogenesis in the absence of an amino acid mutation. LRRK2 gene muta-\ntions, without amino acid changes but with altered protein expression, have also been identiﬁed as\nrisk factors for PD by GWAS [14–17]. Consistently, increasing studies have revealed elevated", page:2}}, {_id:2514, properties:{chunk_index:1, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p2::1::21a932f5", embedding:[0.06033096, 0.090260394, -0.12743615, 0.0038924015, 0.056688346, -0.044054307, 0.008490894, 0.057097506, 0.02042671, -0.025343537, -0.03854872, 0.052780572, 0.088854045, 0.023611961, 0.01598864, -0.029579893, -0.0078092944, -0.0069586337, -0.0129115665, 0.07655266, -0.101871684, -0.02688616, 0.03816623, -0.031209752, 0.063649185, 0.074660756, -0.016854191, 0.005429089, -0.010507068, 0.060208388, 0.05293481, -0.024417628, -0.043382015, -0.024225727, -0.03620979, -0.06859047, 0.1044767, 0.060786974, 0.0068699913, 0.013406177, 0.021410765, 0.04500424, -0.0028945308, -0.035882916, -0.023959706, 0.047434606, 0.0022657397, 0.011987983, 0.028172093, -0.070839174, 0.080268204, -0.0064504966, 0.025642678, -0.0507194, 0.13071749, 0.04111134, -0.046175566, 0.0024444659, 0.022331532, -0.018835654, 0.10255445, 0.05053099, -0.05871937, -0.015466659, 0.039175373, -0.045883544, -0.024666525, 0.053450614, -0.012508359, -0.012784313, 0.039657455, -0.0041372334, -0.0013474906, 0.035688415, -0.02201073, -0.0024953217, 0.020442396, 0.013740695, -0.011169055, 0.01696912, -0.016593413, 0.0073478506, 0.0450045, 0.0073220576, 0.020906737, 0.015813082, -0.021619014, 0.018287748, 0.022140287, 0.069721416, 0.0076907384, 0.012152041, 0.0018909179, -0.019439213, -0.018930875, 0.033545334, 0.024128502