0.03321346, 0.064881034, 0.05902524, -0.043806892, 0.006119525, 0.017571768, -0.02728798, 0.026910247, -0.04757047, -0.065749235, -0.046722226, -0.01230104, -0.009707024, 0.0048797443, 0.02631922, 0.004083887, -0.0173305, 0.0140749775, 0.01449206, -0.035771407, -0.05521371, 0.011202014, -5.5244874E-4, 0.0058265715, 0.022468857, -0.006435199, 0.022795739, 0.026656035, 0.013676661, 0.01781383, -0.03940449, 0.03845541, 0.003871293, 0.029994799, -0.018349126, -0.011641884, -0.046735387, -0.018351438, -0.052615963, -0.057995576, 0.030494202, -0.023354126, -0.038835257, -0.022662083, -0.019011658, -0.014402505, -0.0022529233, 0.016678827, 0.014877558, -0.02964178, 0.05463669, 0.0013587846, -0.001603159, -0.010945561, 0.031252638, 0.008860965, 0.024511999, 0.042008948, 0.013592518, -0.032809492, -0.022119725, -0.024678556, -0.0059415284, 0.009029442, 0.046475004, 0.016078344, 0.053633966, 0.015697788, -0.051927928, -0.013565426, 0.023299979, 0.0072748535, -0.020822346, -0.081013344, -0.011924218, 0.0010014514, 0.006109199, 0.0690983, -0.02520168, 0.024418795, 0.024079913, -0.042959034, -0.008470101, -0.026478313, -0.008664997, -0.041424587, 0.03659937, -0.012513202, 5.109393E-4, -0.06833949, -0.028713305, -0.05209263, 0.01215786, -0.015065329, 0.03593887, -0.009391674, 0.015075907, -0.0019905812, 0.03791378, 0.062924564, 0.020236148, 0.0036212222, 0.059741933, -0.019944426, 0.037241142, -0.0065890807, -0.008100987, -0.056199122, 0.01623926, 0.046459, -0.013908018, 0.05170446, -0.007346173, 0.016984273, -0.032488555, -0.040993944, -0.0333652, -0.020928033, -0.05235191], text:"Upstream regulation of LRRK2\nHow does LRRK2 become activated at the molecular and cellular level? As mentioned earlier,\nextensive work has focused on understanding LRRK2 enzymatic functions, but how are the\ntwo enzymatic activities regulated? What are their downstream targets, and what are the cellular\nconsequences? In this section we ﬁrst discuss the upstream regulation of LRRK2, encompassing\nprotein enzymatic functions, mRNA levels, and protein stability.\nRegulation of LRRK2 kinase activity\nA major feature of LRRK2 is its kinase activity that mediates phosphorylation of a group of\nsubstrates including autophosphorylation at multiple sites. A subset of Rab small GTPases are\nbone ﬁde kinase substrates for LRRK2. The extensively studied autophosphorylation site\npSer1292 is widely recognized as a readout for LRRK2 kinase activity [35], and pSer910 and\npSer935 are phosphorylation sites in the N-terminus that are abundant and mediate LRRK2 bind-\ning to 14-3-3 [36] (Figure 1). Notably, several LRRK2 pathogenic mutants (e.g., R1441G/G/H and\nY1699C) demonstrate reduced levels of pSer935, decreased LRRK2:14-3-3 binding, and conse-\nquently increased kinase activity [36,37], while LRRK2 kinase inhibitors, which block its kinase ac-\ntivity, can abolish phosphorylation of pSer910 and pSer935 and promote 14-3-3 release [38]. This\ndiscrepancy may arise from the differential binding of 14-3-3 and conformational changes of\nLRRK2 caused by the pathogenic mutations, whereas LRRK2 inhibitors destabilize LRRK2, thus\nreducing the total amount of the protein. Dephosphorylation of pSer910/935 results in LRRK2\nrelocalization to the cytosol and accumulation on microtubules [38,39]. Whether the G2019S\nmutation also results in a reduction of LRRK2:14-3-3 binding is not conclusive [37,40]. These\ndata indicate that LRRK2:14-3-3 binding is crucial in LRRK2 kinase activation.\nHow does LRRK2 become activated? LRRK2 cycles between a monomeric cytosolic state with", page:3}}, {_id:2520, properties:{chunk_index:1, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p3::1::2d3a9154", embedding:[-0.031656783, 0.075696036, -0.14142992, -0.017630497, 0.08636625, -0.03631934, 0.036652654, 0.033799265, 0.02245314, -0.017270021, -0.06628174, 0.06571204, 0.099907756, 0.00626421, 0.038402703, -0.06506408, -0.057662927, -0.0131312385, -0.0061158184, 0.06639681, -0.096707925, -0.010281706, 0.022256915, -0.04