933597, 0.025666218, -0.013303909, -0.0011885591, -0.049095977, -0.02254546, 0.055493474, 0.018050348, -0.006277315, -0.07921834, 0.0133992, -0.023833327, 0.03182196, -0.054289933, 0.016168324, -0.049494028, 0.04811661, 0.030733408, -0.003861751, -6.676741E-4, 0.0678884, 0.039036863, -0.03606354, 0.0076726116, 0.08585526, 0.035330508, -0.0047130734, 0.046816878, 0.052639384, -0.040074196, 0.029859979, 0.0046626674, -0.028657997, 0.0016443268, -0.08162144, -0.050963886, -0.003147202, -0.00878628, -0.01963604, -0.020885214, -0.008168974, -0.015487889, -0.005126359, -0.009872041, 0.042541523, -0.023462497, -0.0901297, 0.010104138, 0.010052343, 0.01003156, -0.0047796383, -0.017442191, -0.0017700279, 0.059736963, 0.0062605264, 0.034483027, -0.028987318, 0.015504291, 0.005533228, 0.027395241, -0.013486744, -0.032801412, -0.039809838, -0.0166076, -0.03155156, -0.033612512, 0.024027897, 0.010355188, -0.041865245, -0.03837933, -0.0048266766, 0.009461685, 0.03488846, 0.008339771, 0.014264516, -0.03386662, 0.06676831, -0.03848008, -0.011865146, -0.012319635, -0.0026180944, 0.025835168, 0.027104624, 0.006961958, 0.0014771118, -0.05119965, -0.022221088, -0.008129688, 0.0077449083, -0.016428556, 0.050639227, 0.012500643, 0.010770951, -0.028624466, -0.024380244, -6.1662553E-4, 0.023581997, 0.014143728, -0.021642495, -0.056521624, -0.0087835, -0.030571323, -0.022961667, 0.069183454, -0.021337967, 0.022284767, 0.030683395, -0.059952684, -0.017576287, -0.031756338, 0.015305019, -0.048263557, 0.018607603, 0.0041889786, -0.0047279866, -0.025324121, -0.008427062, -0.056156434, 0.026677163, 0.0011354146, 0.003147729, 9.778277E-4, 0.01926674, -0.012621554, 0.059762422, 0.034600485, -0.001701224, 0.008415715, 0.028583849, -0.009910729, 0.027001258, 0.007357719, 0.007874739, -0.015834654, 0.011045698, 0.03767912, -0.013068466, 0.037577927, -0.009133107, 3.1339342E-4, -8.644184E-4, -0.023949957, 0.017650519, -0.023853917, -0.047866195], text:"data indicate that LRRK2:14-3-3 binding is crucial in LRRK2 kinase activation.\nHow does LRRK2 become activated? LRRK2 cycles between a monomeric cytosolic state with\nlow kinase activity and a dimeric membrane-bound state with high kinase activity [41]. Higher-\norder dimerization/oligomerization and membrane recruitment appear to be required for LRRK2 ac-\ntivation [41–43]. The ﬁrst question then arises: what promotes LRRK2 dimerization/oligomerization?\nStructural studies have provided several insights into this question. The ROC-COR tandem domain\nis particularly important for LRRK2 dimerization. PD-associated pathogenic mutants, such as\nR1441C, are located at the interface of two monomers and stabilize the ROC dimer [44]. Nucleotide\nbinding to the ROC domain may regulate the dimerization of LRRK2, thereby enhancing its kinase\nactivity [45,46]. In addition, nucleotide binding to the ROC domain may intramolecularly enhance\nits interaction with the kinase domain to modulate its kinase activity, a potential allosteric regulatory\nmechanism governing LRRK2 kinase activity [47]. Moreover, loss of LRRK2:14-3-3 binding leads to\ndestabilization of the LRRK2 inactive conformation and enhanced kinase activity [38]. The WD40\ndomain, together with N-terminal domains, traps LRRK2 in an inactive monomer state, while binding\nof various Rab proteins to the N-terminal Armadillo (ARM) domain, which extends to the LRRK2\ndimeric core, breaks this trap and induces LRRK2 membrane translocation [48]. The next question\nconcerns what promotes the recruitment of LRRK2 to membranes. Several small Rab GTPases\nhave been reported to facilitate the recruitment of LRRK2 to the membrane system, subsequently\nactivating LRRK2 kinase activity (Figure 2, Key ﬁgure). Rab29, also known as Rab7L1 and a PD\nrisk factor, recruits LRRK2 to the Golgi complex and increases LRRK2 kinase activity when over-\nexpressed [49–52]. Rab29 induces an unexpected tetrameric assembly of LRRK2 and boosts", page:3}}, {_id:2522, properties:{chunk_index:2, id