03600573, -0.020952694, 0.047048002, 0.06470606, 0.050281227, -0.013448851, 0.04535296, -0.0037605048, 0.040209766, -0.0122882305, -0.017789233, -0.07001826, 0.037622623, 0.06293231, -0.006973315, 0.033119015, -0.028063728, 0.01927194, -0.020025829, 0.014268565, -0.033082467, -0.041010354, -0.026096022], text:"risk factor, recruits LRRK2 to the Golgi complex and increases LRRK2 kinase activity when over-\nexpressed [49–52]. Rab29 induces an unexpected tetrameric assembly of LRRK2 and boosts\npS1292 autophosphorylation [49]. However, endogenous Rab29 does not impact LRRK2 activity\n[53]. More recently, endogenous Rab12 and Rab38 have been reported to bind to LRRK2 [54–56].\nRab12 recruits LRRK2 to damaged lysosomes, whereas Rab38 recruits LRRK2 to the pericentriolar\nregion, both acting as crucial activators that stimulate Rab10 phosphorylation by LRRK2 [54–56].\nRab32, mutation of which has been recently linked to PD, likely activates LRRK2 to stimulate\nRab10 phosphorylation [57,58]. Intriguingly, Rab8 and Rab10 as LRRK2 kinase substrates can\nTrends in Molecular Medicine\n984\nTrends in Molecular Medicine, October 2024, Vol. 30, No. 10", page:3}}, {_id:2523, properties:{chunk_index:0, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p4::0::6e7d570a", embedding:[2.734114E-4, 0.07486378, -0.14678097, -0.015901517, 0.0582055, -0.04102506, 0.026984226, 0.02091945, 0.0033484849, -0.056182683, -0.049029745, 0.09239676, 0.08825353, 0.0022324969, 0.02072603, -0.05171578, -0.0032125402, -0.014813989, 0.013405616, 0.075463645, -0.0858558, -0.01413225, 0.016883392, -0.042800378, 0.053502984, 0.054985635, 0.053436387, -0.05812127, -0.0096822325, 0.020824656, 0.068488, -0.04319861, -0.0022546116, -0.06249559, -0.05485036, -0.06798753, 0.057599984, 0.030245716, -0.021518009, 0.0077266623, -7.0686545E-4, 0.018545974, 0.023543708, -0.03653985, 0.00330474, -0.0014917282, -0.0063877385, -0.006983263, 0.07265809, -0.058891185, 0.04565705, 0.022899691, -0.008936715, -0.056920018, 0.108993575, 0.0330121