051559806, -0.032799277, 0.0041496977, 0.009597559, 0.0062532052, -0.021384561, -0.006020429, 0.02632254, 0.02928142, 0.02496634, 0.017852055, -0.06507066, 0.032744177, 0.0020772233, 0.04314851, -0.037912063, -0.022939522, -0.041510336, -0.001569835, -0.038328115, -0.054774765, 0.024413686, -0.0049187946, -0.03547736, 0.00983654, -0.034428984, 0.010703949, 0.030446386, 0.030970622, -0.008158916, -0.033208422, 0.058676347, 0.016970078, -0.015753808, 0.008554701, 0.03827489, -2.9415108E-4, 0.00851167, 0.031194266, 0.0148905665, -0.020051396, -0.009355423, 0.007328388, -0.0011073536, -0.024507238, 0.063622214, 0.041744214, 0.028190175, -0.026416354, -0.039794676, 0.012012131, 0.023342552, 0.04137975, -0.029319962, -0.043307517, -0.013512017, -0.018040763, 0.013812547, 0.06693685, -0.026227297, -0.013961585, 0.00423846, -0.029695734, -0.01244736, -0.018789845, -0.041961417, -0.028699746, 0.03227506, -0.021642398, -0.02329643, -0.07303473, -0.015175365, -0.026383517, 0.035848018, -0.0045172637, 0.068067394, -0.0073468448, -0.023358144, -0.02382931, 0.05764174, 0.07671932, -9.984717E-4, -0.019450052, 0.023645172, 0.027202727, 0.040312253, 0.030707937, -0.020351272, -0.027631406, 0.05552164, 0.05871948, 0.0069046407, 0.049270187, -0.011318956, -0.0023843695, -0.011051314, -0.029259339, -0.003289524, -0.025294797, -0.041657843], text:"Regulation of LRRK2 GTPase function\nLRRK2 is a guanine nucleotide-binding protein (G-protein). The mechanism of direct regulation of\nits GTPase function is understudied compared to its kinase function, although pathogenic muta-\ntions in the LRRK2 ROC and COR domains stimulate LRRK2 kinase activity to a greater extent\nthan those in the kinase domain [50,51]. This observation aligns with the fact that R1441C/G\nand Y1699C mutants in the ROC-COR domains exhibit nearly full penetrance compared to\nthe incomplete penetrance of G2019S in the kinase domain, the most prevalent muta-\ntion [62,63]. The mechanism underlying the higher phosphorylation levels induced by LRRK2\nGTPase mutations compared to kinase domain mutations is not clear but could indicate new\nPD-linked mechanisms that have not been well‐investigated. A potential allosteric regulatory\nmechanism via nucleotide binding to the ROC domain intramolecularly enhances its interaction\nwith the kinase domain and may govern LRRK2 kinase activity [47]. Vice versa, LRRK2 kinase\nactivity may reciprocally regulate GTPase activity, as evidenced by in vitro autophosphorylation\nsites that tend to cluster within the ROC domain [64], and which may alter the Michaelis–\nMenten kinetics of the LRRK2 ROC domain, thus affecting the rate of GTPase hydrolysis and\npromoting the formation of ROC dimers [65,66]. However, it remains to be determined how\nautophosphorylation regulates LRRK2 GTPase activity.\nG-proteins are molecular switches in which the 'on' state involves GTP binding whereas the 'off'\nstate involves GDP binding following GTP hydrolysis. This process is typically regulated by\nGTPase-activating proteins (GAPs) and guanine nucleotide exchange factors (GEFs)\n[67] (Figure 3). In addition, one mechanism of activation involves G-proteins activated by\nnucleotide-dependent dimerization (GADs) [68]. Whether LRRK2 is regulated by GAPs\nand GEFs or is a GAD has been debated. Studies using the bacteria Chlorobium tepidum protein", page:5}}, {_id:2526, properties:{chunk_index:1, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p5::1::7b8da2bd", embedding:[-0.007563981, 0.07945498, -0.11662245, -0.032919742, 0.10330999, -0.00921815, -0.0028483684, 0.025001021, 0.03132256, -0.0666615, -0.05631643, 0.046406306, 0.079227194, -0.002350808, 0.029467488, -0.038180392, -0.032069962, -0.0389772, -0.002724549, 0.06283881, -0.074023604, 0.0036954442, 0.039210815, -0.022759218, 0.072503716, 0.042824972, 0.06177638, -0.04888011, 0.014904582, 0.02374938, 0.05753169, -0.021308584, -0.0014429274, 0.010864285, -0.032887302, -0.09166881, 0.058892746, 0.031126237, -0.007886448, -0.002101106, -0