057387292, 0.0388106, -0.021708665, 0.021075753, 0.052333597, -0.004553123, 0.022532443, 0.02329251, 0.0810926, 0.016259432, -0.0062677325, 0.04267332, 0.05607494, -0.049260505, 0.04372085, 0.015710978, 0.0044066743, 0.0066341916, -0.052952297, -0.043183655, -0.011777363, 0.005328326, -0.009845075, -0.0022613013, -3.7558394E-4, -0.009579154, 0.021467656, -0.014606625, 0.048889082, -0.0074702087, -0.04404855, 0.012245429, -0.002365224, 0.0068875644, -0.016395384, 0.031023882, 0.037291817, 0.027465845, -0.017012628, 0.010385573, -0.042934194, 0.03935085, 0.009549012, 0.011154977, -0.041264366, -0.032336768, -0.04405319, -0.0039469413, -0.06429779, -0.019981666, 0.009052299, 0.013197783, -0.021896396, 0.019607412, -0.017733207, -0.014950509, 0.0050365035, 0.03632323, 0.0047589424, -0.029641617, 0.034167722, 0.005756111, -0.018327408, 0.006866693, 0.014835142, 0.0070119565, -0.0065969517, -0.056463085, -7.621102E-5, -0.039679106, -0.035469286, 0.007031704, 0.008075567, -0.049112193, 0.037566002, 0.014722358, -0.037761535, -0.038972244, -0.04862484, 0.028848046, 0.035141014, -0.0053989636, -0.033914097, -0.038852643, -0.02535227, -0.039510585, -0.015876887, 0.07082699, -0.040588234, -0.008494939, 0.017590657, -0.04228053, -0.004856191, -0.012685974, -0.021307573, -0.06377314, 0.022400467, -4.916709E-4, -0.015408932, -0.104441375, -0.026305357, -0.055798415, 0.05315485, -0.00599326, 0.008983895, 0.0024523523, 0.022542339, -0.046775952, 0.04050699, 0.06379815, 0.0059844214, -0.017988186, 0.021969024, 0.007289181, 0.009436782, 0.04517305, -0.029240973, -0.01794056, 0.07651965, 0.06323935, -0.009332374, 0.027448377, -0.0327255, 0.03256911, 0.00872824, -0.033710286, 0.019233383, -0.021431243, -0.032816518], text:"nucleotide-dependent dimerization (GADs) [68]. Whether LRRK2 is regulated by GAPs\nand GEFs or is a GAD has been debated. Studies using the bacteria Chlorobium tepidum protein\nwith a ROC-COR structure suggest that LRRK2 has the capacity to function as a GAD [69]. How-\never, this study utilized a prokaryote LRRK2 homolog protein, and the structure requires intermo-\nlecular exchange of an arginine residue in trans to generate an active site, but the key arginine is\nnot present in human LRRK2 [70]. The expected behavior of a GAD involves GTP enhancing\ndimerization whereas GDP weakens it. However, the bacterial Roco protein is mainly dimeric in\nthe nucleotide-free and GDP-bound states but forms monomers upon GTP binding [71]. The\nGAD model also does not ﬁt with mammalian LRRK2 because LRRK2 ROC-COR dimerization\nwas not enhanced by GTP or GTPγS in a LRRK2 GTPase-COR self-binding assay [72]. Several\nlines of evidence have demonstrated that the isolated GTPase domain of LRRK2 is catalytically\nactive in its monomeric form, suggesting that dimerization is not required for LRRK2 GTPase\nTrends\nTrends in\nin Molecular\nMolecular Medicine\nMedicine\nFigure 3. Model of the LRRK2\nGTPase function cycle. The LRRK2\nGTPase cycle switches between the\ninactive 'Off' GDP-bound state and\nthe active 'On' GTP-bound state. The\ninactive\nstate\nis\ninduced\nby\nthe\nstimulation of intrinsic GTPase hydrolysis\nactivity through GTPase-activating proteins\n(GAPs), potentially ArfGAP1 and RSG2.\nActivation is facilitated by guanine\nnucleotide exchange factors (GEFs),\npotentially CalDAG-GEFI, which load\nGTP and dissociate GDP, thus enabling\ninteraction with downstream effectors\nand, consequently, activating downstream\nsignaling pathways. The physiological GAPs and GEFs for LRRK2 need to be further conﬁrmed, but they are speculated to\nregulate LRRK2 association with diverse membranes, as do other small GTPases. Abbreviations: COR, C-terminal of ROC\nGTPase; Pi, inorganic phosphate; ROC, Ras of the complex.", page:5}}, {_id:2527, properties:{chunk_index:2, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p5::2::aace8c6a", embedding:[0.0088858, 0.08547897, -0.14443226, -0.041698974, 0.03711309, -0.031208253, 0.022601323, -0.017111864, 0.008934381, -0.047719