9, -0.026015038, 0.048720732, 0.022731224, 0.01840771, 0.012625232, -0.074155994, -0.0063104415, 0.048256848, -0.009334622, -0.029338362, -0.08461161, -0.02506009, -0.014417319, -0.024610696, 0.08839782, -0.017632896, 0.024430646, 0.036577504, -0.048396833, -0.018912528, -0.016536772, -0.025496574, -0.011027977, 0.025371743, -0.043005943, -0.02658587, -0.11868604, -0.020095006, -0.04141771, -0.015556807, 0.003211495, 0.02407986, -0.0064232866, -0.020903451, -0.021121074, 0.05200611, 0.05906537, 0.0055394373, 0.012149983, 0.0012092466, -0.0480951, 0.026528094, -0.0033773375, -0.018348774, -0.024409363, 0.067419276, 0.05577628, -0.0020226245, 0.049654465, -0.040875465, 0.019344248, -0.010920473, -0.047851425, -0.020046584, -0.0057595694, -0.018907653], text:"activity [65,70]. Therefore, the LRRK2 G-protein cycle is not compatible with the GAD model.\nRecent studies using human LRRK2 proteins suggest that LRRK2 GTPase activity requires\nboth GAPs and GEFs because of its low intrinsic catalytic activity but high-afﬁnity binding of\nGTP/GDP [70,73]. Supporting this notion is the fact that ArfGAP1 functions as a GAP candi-\ndate for LRRK2 and can regulate LRRK2 GTPase hydrolysis and toxicity [74,75]. The RGS2\nGAP also regulates LRRK2 GTP hydrolysis and protects against LRRK2 mutation-induced\nneurite shortening and neuronal toxicity [76]. Another study identiﬁed an interaction of\nLRRK2 with ARHGEF7 [77]. Intriguingly, this study showed that ARHGEF7 increases both\nLRRK2 GTP-binding activity and GTP hydrolysis, suggesting that ARHGEF7 may have both\nLRRK2 GEF and GAP functions. Thus, it is not clear whether ARHGEF7 is a GEF or GAP\nfor LRRK2. Caution should be taken because these proposed GAPs and GEFs do not bind\ndirectly to the GTPase domain of LRRK2, as would be expected for small GTPases. Recently,\nCalDAG-GEFI has been identiﬁed as a potential physiological GEF candidate for LRRK2 (Q. Liu\net al., unpublished). CalDAG-GEFI directly binds to the LRRK2 GTPase domain, increases its\nGDP to GTP exchange activity, and modulates LRRK2 cellular functions and LRRK2-\ninduced neurodegeneration in both LRRK2 Drosophila and mouse models. This study together\nwith previous reports provide strong evidence that LRRK2 GTPase activity is regulated by\nGAPs and GEFs (Figure 3).\nRegulation of LRRK2 mRNA levels\nAlthough LRRK2 protein levels play an important role in PD pathogenesis, the regulation of LRRK2\nexpression is an important but understudied area in PD pathogenesis. Until recently there had\nbeen no investigation of how LRRK2 mRNA levels are regulated [33]. This work uncovered a novel\nmechanism of regulation of LRRK2 mRNA levels through adenine/uridine-rich element (ARE)-", page:6}}, {_id:2529, properties:{chunk_index:1, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p6::1::e2c7e1fa", embedding:[0.019132685, 0.09320136, -0.12557516, -0.008013824, 0.075455025, -0.0332263, 0.011318413, 0.05564837, 0.0066030617, -0.05391665, -0.019524818, 0.044028036, 0.09323292, 2.7692554E-4, 0.027353441, -0.017192569, 0.012440411, -0.038872678, -0.008323669, 0.047501497, -0.06876282, -0.016611071, 0.047339108, -0.018203802, 0.055776395, 0.095415406, 0.011323251, -0.026770616, 0.03391014, 0.019108025, 0.083134465, -0.07888986, -0.011293279, 0.0023885365, -0.042465515, -0.061186824, 0.113604546, 0.061820153, 0.0114513775, -0.0048416005, -0.0070028747, 0.023286263, 0.01978969, -0.041857753, -0.018545063, 0.025116088, 0.0086956145, -0.017741429, 0.051949978, -0.05632343, 0.08923699, -0.00151726, -5.3465814E-5, -0.059204634, 0.1441939, 0.015696026, -0.04368041, -5.054375E-4, 0.024521869, 0.046522867, 0.09388474, 0.05812173, -0.016847443, 0.030467961, 0.07066486, -0.06468772, -0.008787789, 0.04350722, -0.009315873, -0.0036141719, 0.021381581, -0.03044711, -0.010973823, 0.03329922, -0.014231763, -0.023561092, 0.035920627, 0.0021029925, -0.017400835, 0.017885143, -0.033389315, -0.004524048, 0.06406628, 0.054530818, 0.0061791693, -5.652825E-4, -0.073139615, -0.014087496, -0.0