, 0.028820481, 0.035531648, 0.03307498, -5.7534105E-4, 0.04521263, -0.029039983, 0.0044215103, 0.049350057, 0.029374698, 0.018049974, 0.02430137, 0.014662195, 0.03599741, -0.03627707, 0.026100507, 0.0336198, 0.05333166, 0.004354825, 0.03601337, 0.026373938, 0.040610958, 0.044725105, -0.037284486, -0.007046378, 0.054652356, 0.0022510835, -0.017116753, -0.04695494, -0.01500916, -0.010227746, -0.042936455, 0.04865582, -0.017774034, -0.013961351, 5.2018417E-4, -0.057765137, -0.012149134, -0.02110214, -0.0019246347, -0.014958733, 0.024731593, -0.004663718, -0.045740414, -0.06163874, -0.032110218, -0.020947546, -0.0018645375, -0.02304799, 0.03512878, -0.039821062, 0.002946153, -0.022352379, 0.026869299, 0.08006436, 0.03264598, 0.043295797, -0.010866489, -0.06797253, 0.04297589, 0.015396815, -0.016369903, 0.016752243, 0.041658223, 0.061167136, -0.010682524, 0.034619857, -0.046023138, 0.061856315, 0.02518575, -0.018980158, -0.01432111, -0.04914492, 0.012258404], text:"and the LRRK2-mediated regulation of the microtubule-binding protein tau [102,103]. Microtu-\nbules play vital roles in vesicular and organellar transport speciﬁcally in DA neurons, where\ntransport and communication between cell bodies and distant growth cones occur via long\naxon microtubules. The microtubule-associated E3 ligase TRIM1 appears to be crucially involved\nin LRRK2 degradation [81]. Given the LRRK2 function in endolysosomal trafﬁcking with micro-\ntubule binding, it could suggest that LRRK2 mutations impair microtubule-based endolysosomal\ntrafﬁcking in axons, which may partially explain the selective vulnerability in DA neurons.\nMitochondrial function\nMitochondria, the powerhouse of the cell, have functions that are heavily implicated in PD pathogen-\nesis. Despite several studies reporting that LRRK2 mutations elicit abnormalities in mitochondrial mor-\nphology [104,105] and mitochondrial DNA damage [106,107], evidence for a direct interaction\nbetween LRRK2 and mitochondrial function is limited. LRRK2 might be transiently localized on the mi-\ntochondrial membrane and interact with the mitochondrial ﬁssion protein DLP1 [108]. Another line of\nevidence is that wild-type LRRK2 is recruited to the mitochondrial outer membrane in human induced\npluripotent stem cell (iPSC)-derived neurons treated with the mitochondrial depolarizing agents anti-\nmycin A and CCCP, and this promotes the physical interaction of LRRK2 with the outer mitochondrial\nmembrane protein MIRO [109]. MIRO, as a tether, attaches damaged mitochondria to axon microtu-\nbules, leading to their removal by mitophagy [109]. Because LRRK2 binds to microtubules and reg-\nulates ER–mitochondria tethering as described in the preceding text, LRRK2 could play important\nroles at interorganelle contacts or at the crossroads of ER, mitochondria, and microtubules.\nCell non-autonomous functions\nLRRK2 plays an important role in the periphery, and this may also contribute to PD pathogenesis.", page:8}}, {_id:2536, properties:{chunk_index:2, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p8::2::22ec1127", embedding:[0.029324967, 0.057086732, -0.13797039, -0.055993058, 0.05397558, -0.039711792, 0.023646072, 0.038057115, 0.059518702, -0.037005212, -0.030288756, 0.030369243, 0.08681113, 0.053177826, 0.044128764, -0.028007317, -0.07592245, -0.002545976, 0.003098618, 0.026171, -0.051322754, -0.00786911, 0.062329605, 0.0059638917, 0.09200114, 0.13409176, 0.025530936, -0.064639054, -0.0011081048, 0.007980322, 0.092820644, -0.025198977, -0.012335208, -0.039342813, 0.011790053, -0.006775057, 0.05602556, 0.020397156, -0.017442996, 0.039999664, -0.074612245, 0.022469448, 0.040432807, -0.05678885, 0.014722284, 0.049408708, 0.02074228, 0.0025265552, 0.03021751, -0.074853204, 0.026824163, -0.018058129, 0.011486847, -0.038924627, 0.086855896, -0.037351977, 0.053644847, -0.043588758, 0.03334264, -0.0033658491, 0.08109197, 0.05742127, -0.054547645, 0.013392711, 0.0067333532, -0.03622595, -0.04105728, 0.015507633, -0.026927559, -0.0511