5252947, 0.03208835, 0.03518194, 0.027516657, -0.033560935, -0.03231727, 0.027294878, 0.029079674, -0.020952554, -0.05461972, -0.048135445, 0.010826952, 0.023326889, -0.07117575, 0.0022175547, -2.0841534E-4, 0.0030231911, 0.013189258, -0.050449472, -0.05575362, -0.04220609, 0.004309638, -0.03449361, 0.0051675313, -0.06899448, -0.038872615, -0.046056278, 0.0029617725, -0.037104208, -0.0049709207, -0.011108062, 0.018735185, -0.009420888, 0.016960846, -0.013933825, 0.046607826, 0.03270772, -0.0024528413, 0.05707782, 0.055450574, -0.049978647, 0.028988993, -0.009397903, 0.0013433866, -0.009597538, 0.007969442, 0.07284824, 0.012810148, 0.051976588, -0.040986072, 0.029324712, 0.054485, -0.039549105, -0.008082335, 0.0067713573, -0.06250406], text:"type I inhibitors that bind to the ATP pocket, representing the active and closed conformation of\nthe kinase. Highly potent, brain-penetrant, and selective compounds such as GNE7915, GNE-\n0877 (also known as DNL201) [117,122], PF-475 [123], PF-360 [124], and MLi-2 [125] have\nbeen developed (Figure 5). DNL201 and its relative DNL151/BIIB122 have moved to clinical trials\nto evaluate tolerability and target engagement [28,117]. DNL201 has undergone evaluation in\nPhase 1 and 1b studies and demonstrated inhibition of LRRK2 at single and multiple doses, and\nwas well tolerated at doses indicative of LRRK2 pathway engagement [117]. DNL151/BIIB122 is\nadvancing to Phase 2b efﬁcacy studies in the LUMA (NCT05348785) trial in early-stage iPD pa-\ntients and LRRK2 variant carriers through a collaboration between Biogen and Denali Therapeutics,\nalthough the full potential off-target effects of DNL151/BIIB122 are not yet clear [126].\nAn ideal inhibitor must be highly speciﬁc for LRRK2, potent, brain-penetrant, easily administered,\nand safe for prolonged use. However, almost all type I LRRK2 inhibitors to date have not met all\nthese criteria. In addition, type I LRRK2 inhibitors target the closed conformation of the kinase\nwhich has been reported to oligomerize LRRK2 on microtubules [103]. This implies that inhibition\nof LRRK2 by type I inhibitors can block microtubule-based motors and, consequently, block\nlysosomal dynamics. Therefore, an alternative solution could be the development of type II kinase\ninhibitors that target and stabilize an inactive and open form of LRRK2. Three type II kinase inhibitors,\nnamely rebastinib, ponatinib, and GZD-824, have been reported to target LRRK2 but are not selec-\ntive and have a broad kinase target spectrum [48,103,127]. One natural variant of vitamin B12,\nAdoCbl, acts as a 'mixed-type allosteric inhibitor' of LRRK2 kinase activity. Unlike type I LRRK2\nkinase inhibitors, AdoCbl does not compete with ATP for the active site of LRRK2 and instead", page:9}}, {_id:2541, properties:{chunk_index:2, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p9::2::5a130a1b", embedding:[-0.002825869, 0.058743462, -0.16491978, 0.028172519, 0.061526403, -0.046080258, 0.047027554, 0.032479305, 0.015085551, -0.047859542, -0.014859587, 0.045648545, 0.10836159, -0.016803447, -0.005315098, -0.062996715, -0.016547512, -0.03803144, 0.005709559, 0.08845607, -0.0699011, -0.009227601, -0.02716665, -0.07316862, -0.0011434818, 0.06780611, 0.014158989, -0.022048807, -5.4316805E-4, 0.048238393, 0.07676971, -0.030813647, -0.024508938, -0.008915994, -0.046312913, -0.06460402, 0.059130747, 0.04317268, -0.030473609, -0.009581688, 0.030366613, 0.026821127, 0.053979415, -0.023744851, 0.014798686, 0.021504244, -0.0138814505, 0.030003183, 0.05231924, -0.07664657, 0.051053114, -0.009450157, -0.010674853, -0.030766968, 0.109829396, -0.014469505, -0.054509975, -0.013496465, -0.022797313, -0.04697404, 0.052504364, 0.04403845, -0.07458102, -0.0025369395, 0.06298634, -0.069009274, -0.043475512, 0.037629306, 0.010458522, -0.06308089, 0.055169433, -7.6615217E-4, 0.030798625, 0.03740806, -0.0309551, 0.003155408, 0.0052246545, 0.0034150141, 0.04418743, -0.005024746, 0.022203393, -0.019010264, 0.08756427, 0.02723479, 0.0