01208591, 0.0024155113, 0.031844787, 0.044445876, -0.0062505812, -0.012708357, -0.011119466, -0.0129619995, 0.019908091, -0.0021198662, 0.038616944, 0.018654356, 0.040511865, -0.006467565, -0.063259326, 0.0114906905, 0.030817803, -0.0034771275, -0.045014102, -0.05862692, -0.032640778, -0.013778102, 0.012437214, 0.06988303, -0.03969521, -0.015297205, -0.028030125, -0.012702102, -0.025327004, -0.030989086, -0.0015998534, -0.039065544, 0.015753895, -0.054982524, 0.0065124207, -0.062233858, -0.039445408, -0.03517913, 0.0043399697, 0.006378318, 0.065577656, -0.002509979, 0.006368125, -0.019951345, 0.055712342, 0.05749247, 0.030306112, 0.0025112361, 0.046025183, -0.028132956, 0.019134076, -0.0067914487, -4.9413535E-5, -0.0119048115, 0.04769572, 0.06178062, -5.700442E-4, 0.056037825, -0.01919402, 0.016325133, -0.009503163, -0.04158301, 0.0022902347, -0.026025156, -0.0728279], text:"Despite the major milestones in LRRK2 kinase inhibitor development mentioned previously, the fact\nthat different LRRK2 pathogenic mutants behave differently in substrate phosphorylation suggests a\ncomplex biology of LRRK2 that is not well understood [130] (Box 1). Whether LRRK2 kinase activity is\nat the core of LRRK2 biology inﬂuencing PD progression remains an open question. Alternative strat-\negies that circumvent the adverse effects observed in LRRK2 kinase inhibition should be considered.\nTargeting LRRK2 GTPase activity\nIn addition to LRRK2 kinase activity, LRRK2 function is also regulated by its GTPase domain which\nacts upstream of kinase activity. This is particularly noteworthy given that the most penetrant LRRK2\nmutant, R1441C, lies within the GTPase domain. LRRK2 GTPase activity may play a central role in\nLRRK2 function [131,132]. The protective variant R1398H shows lower GTP binding but increased\nhydrolysis, suggesting potential beneﬁts in stimulating LRRK2 GTPase activity and decreasing GTP-\nbinding ability [133]. Theoretically, potential therapeutic approaches could include developing LRRK2\nGTPase modulators by directly targeting LRRK2 GTPase activity. Because LRRK2 GEFs increase\nLRRK2 GTP-binding activity and increase kinase activity, the development of LRRK2 GEF inhibitors\nmay be an impressive means to modulate LRRK2 activity and toxicity. Conversely, enhancing the\nGAP function of LRRK2 could be an alternative approach. Caution should be taken because\nTrends\nTrends in\nin Molecular\nMolecular Medicine\nMedicine\nFigure 4. Regulation of LRRK2 mRNA decay by an ATIC–AICAR–AUF1 axis. Knockout of a purine biosynthesis\nenzyme ATIC [5-aminoimidazole-4-carboxamide ribonucleotide (AICAR) formyltransferase/IMP cyclohydrolase] or\nadministration of AICAr (AICA ribonucleoside) increases the intracellular AICAR/ZMP level, which in turn facilitates AU-rich\nelement RNA-binding protein 1 (AUF1) binding to LRRK2 mRNA. AUF1 binds to the AU-rich element of LRRK2 which", page:10}}, {_id:2545, properties:{chunk_index:1, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p10::1::87a9599f", embedding:[0.025372954, 0.067114696, -0.122350425, -0.02313482, 0.12079937, -0.008478819, 0.0056709168, 0.07377601, 0.027925817, -0.03180176, -0.018362027, 0.0994891, 0.08081896, -0.020840317, 0.04422622, -0.012278561, 0.021114275, -0.055285, -0.039365765, 0.024925085, -0.07209593, 6.657085E-4, 0.039046295, -0.032157898, 0.041504476, 0.082949355, 0.030323407, -3.4052003E-4, -0.05409191, 0.026123883, 0.07772713, -0.06477636, -0.008430119, -0.0340357, -0.032868024, -0.015943699, 0.057618164, 0.083410986, 0.0030357426, -0.015543308, -0.03247702, 0.012143547, 0.04002989, -0.051253688, 0.028527057, 0.03925929, 0.007329379, -0.03009123, 0.050231453, -0.09466168, 0.07209798, -0.011477516, -0.027212806, -0.024458574, 0.096653916, 0.008773772, -0.017946057, -0.022630403, 0.011577797, 0.02172563, 0.08807267, 0.090180986, -0.053602036, 0.021719486, 0.04835688, -0.054445535, -0.020332517, 0.06563051, -0.025187278, -0.024515258, 0.015147266, -0.014619601, -0.008813019, 0.019169465, 4.1658286E-