, -0.017212661, -0.024851304, -0.030798007, -0.03529337, 0.038803253, -0.06995857, -0.03081022, -0.10707545, -0.019145366, -0.009895498, -0.0071341977, 0.0050373087, 0.037576005, -0.04870922, 0.015669398, -0.01682486, 0.035322387, 0.029114256, 0.02517333, 0.023955617, 0.02089693, -0.036455866, 0.05462548, 0.014498073, -0.0029631574, -0.0014211526, 0.015634175, 0.052107777, 0.013959888, 0.03428506, -0.034612782, 0.01476526, 0.019133111, -0.051980786, 9.85509E-5, -0.005614123, -0.058704983], text:"LRRK2 GEFs and GAPs are likely to regulate other proteins and processes, suggesting potential\noff-target effects. Other possible targets include blocking the GTP-binding pocket of the LRRK2\nGTPase domain by small compounds [134] and targeting the dimer structure of LRRK2 GTPase\ndomain ROC-COR to block the dimer interface and allosterically modulate LRRK2 kinase activity\nby constrained peptides [135,136]. In contrast to small-molecule inhibitors, these stapled peptides\ncan target elongated binding surfaces that are typically unsuited to small molecules. LRRK2\nGTPase activity is undoubtedly a crucial target and should gain more attention. However, it\nhas been extremely difﬁcult to pharmacologically modulate its selectivity for small GTPases,\nand the COR domain, to date, has no identiﬁed sites for binding small molecules, making it dif-\nﬁcult to therapeutically modulate LRRK2 by this route [137].\nTargeting LRRK2 levels\nIncreasing studies have revealed elevated LRRK2 protein expression in some familial and\nsporadic cases of PD [14–16,18–21]. Destabilization of LRRK2 presents an attractive approach to\nlimit its detrimental effects (Figure 5). One approach is to employ antisense oligonucleotides (ASOs)\nto target LRRK2 mRNA for degradation. Preclinical investigations demonstrated that this approach re-\nduced LRRK2 protein levels and ﬁbril-induced α-synuclein inclusions [29]. Intracerebral injection of\nLRRK2 ASOs avoids unwanted phenotypes associated with loss of LRRK2 expression in the periph-\nery. The LRRK2 ASO inhibitor BIIB094 is in the ongoing Phase 1 study REASON (NCT03976349). As\nmentioned before, DNL151/BIIB122 has been reported to reduce total LRRK2 protein levels [28], sug-\ngesting that DNL151/BIIB122 inhibits LRRK2 kinase activity and decreases LRRK2 protein levels.\nFurthermore, a recent study found that a purine biosynthesis enzyme ATIC and its substrate\nAICAR/ZMP regulate LRRK2 mRNA levels and LRRK2-induced DA neurodegeneration and neuro-", page:11}}, {_id:2547, properties:{chunk_index:1, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p11::1::f141b35d", embedding:[0.008282668, 0.08716174, -0.12113513, -0.03103729, 0.08245757, -0.060100455, -0.016861364, 0.064230025, -0.002839529, -0.031773582, 0.012256662, 0.04213895, 0.07291441, 0.0022041057, 0.04025731, -0.03085824, 0.0042888485, -0.0634892, -0.0025343655, 0.07234153, -0.07782513, -0.02604501, 0.044847928, -0.015093285, 0.045685943, 0.08313057, 0.005127589, -0.011827091, 0.029196985, 0.03527179, 0.09208473, -0.054402363, -0.012404201, 0.012212435, -0.015244865, -0.07675478, 0.0824526, 0.029145487, 0.020971965, -0.019168036, 0.0021808983, 0.0029801088, 0.043836556, -0.08647206, 0.013864359, 0.02846522, 0.020172974, -0.022745755, 0.04358057, -0.08063265, 0.091796674, -0.009732344, -0.0037029602, -0.050587576, 0.12265546, -0.00942827, 0.0013843507, -0.042938285, 0.030686192, 0.020008098, 0.082708, 0.060454533, 2.2751756E-4, 0.051101424, 0.08897045, -0.07664968, -0.02444842, 0.028081456, -0.0026223494, -0.04134596, 0.043409668, -0.004680608, 0.00760074, 0.038801428, -0.0015480324, -0.034707602, 0.030002365, -0.03237823, -0.022881085, 0.0031162924, -0.04549224, -0.025331005, 0.059944652, 0.044862203, -0.00544994, -0.00613567, -0.044873618, -0.023817113, -0.03806916, 0.0568571, -0.00894947, 0.014844434, -0.006192684, -0.006995912, -0.046885926, 0.037766997, 0.03856573, 0.0203686, -0.024357554, 0.0030131545, -0.03653554, -0.029929971, 0.02755662, -0.028044334, 0.035180885, 0.061805