, -0.018227454, 0.0061735143, 0.01838247, -0.023980323, -9.4398274E-4, -0.028389527, -0.011489385, 0.023898521, -0.028710164, 0.02343995, -7.157327E-4, 0.029346628, -0.001229146, -0.043183606, 0.010329163, 0.045648213, -0.005947577, 0.0030693226, -0.08576477, -0.014440711, 0.0027170836, -0.021320399, 0.09260784, -0.01781436, -0.022987526, 0.012704297, -0.011906914, 0.0013637776, -0.017293533, -0.0012669326, -0.002398996, 0.041149013, -0.0626214, -0.028272934, -0.09703353, -0.016120767, -0.019026091, -0.011218739, -0.02392761, -0.009921627, -0.0106739495, 0.031583555, -0.009180359, 0.06143087, 0.057667486, 1.6835533E-4, 0.03697847, -0.0026295655, -0.025321178, 0.05615829, 0.0072322628, -0.009942802, 0.048345417, 0.0571883, 0.05917052, -0.004033575, 0.02422077, -0.048348956, 0.032895967, -2.0566268E-4, -0.07678829, -0.014855599, 0.005404707, -0.021106236], text:"Furthermore, a recent study found that a purine biosynthesis enzyme ATIC and its substrate\nAICAR/ZMP regulate LRRK2 mRNA levels and LRRK2-induced DA neurodegeneration and neuro-\ninﬂammation in PD animal models [33]. This study provides a novel avenue to use endogenous\nways to target LRRK2 mRNA decay and, in turn, reduce LRRK2 levels. This ﬁnding allows the de-\nvelopment of therapeutic compounds that use the body's own regulatory mechanisms to control\nLRRK2, which may minimize any adverse side effects. AICAr, the cell-permeable precursor of\nAICAR, could be used as a tool compound alongside ASOs to explore the effects of decreasing\nLRRK2 levels. Another approach is to develop LRRK2 proteolysis-targeting chimeras (PROTACs)\nto target LRRK2 protein for degradation. The PROTAC degrader XL01126 has been reported to\nbe orally bioavailable and brain-penetrant, and demonstrated fast and potent degradation of\nLRRK2 [34], and an MLi-2-based degrader JH-XII-03-02 displayed high potency and remarkable\nselectivity for LRRK2 [138]. These provide an alternative LRRK2-targeting strategy and a suitable\ndegrader probe to study the noncatalytic and scaffolding functions of LRRK2. Targeting at both\nthe mRNA and protein levels are very promising pharmacological approaches because loss of\nLRRK2 function in humans is not associated with any disease phenotype [139].\nLRRK2 could be targeted in more ways. In addition to LRRK2 enzymatic activities and protein\nlevels, the crucial cellular interactors of LRRK2 could also be targeted as valuable therapeutics\n(Figure 5). Constrained peptides targeting Rab–RILPL interactions have been developed to down-\nregulate pathogenic signaling mediated by LRRK2 and restore ciliogenesis and centrosomal cohe-\nsion defects [140].\nConcluding remarks\nWe are witnessing an exciting time for the LRRK2 ﬁeld, although it has always been complex.\nLRRK2 lies at the nexus of signaling pathways and presents an attractive target. Although deﬁning", page:11}}, {_id:2548, properties:{chunk_index:2, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p11::2::78418982", embedding:[0.006992525, 0.083665855, -0.13072506, -0.009064064, 0.07992988, -0.03363206, 0.053006753, 0.012880374, 0.03491481, -0.05224315, -0.021659594, 0.07412425, 0.11513914, 0.00650509, 0.021924121, -0.0596888, -0.0013636439, -0.0039372277, -0.015865576, 0.046362724, -0.05286162, -0.011650973, 0.011954251, -0.027192557, 0.03814267, 0.08380525, -0.016633522, -0.018791405, 0.012892761, 0.022143714, 0.106317155, -0.027745107, -0.022807041, -0.023189051, -0.045712873, -0.038002025, 0.04960435, 0.022993932, 0.015542593, 5.6366032E-5, 0.013234902, 2.4702612E-4, 0.0012684395, -0.0693988, 0.0036232602, 0.049837258, 0.03745699, -0.027841229, 0.068800725, -0.09072529, 0.028445488, 0.0010304935, 4.4603684E-4, -0.024475072, 0.10156673, -0.0022387013, -0.006549338, -0.0119839795, 0.006116793, 0.012125115, 0.08969152, 0.08224912, -0.04328946, -0.017366624, 0.043091305, -0.06864097, -0.009867815, 0.051059764, -0.01969326, -0.07226119, 0.079607904, -0.03636483, -0.010123895, 0.04206058, -0.019460374, -0.009076142, 0.055036094, -0