.048042443, -0.027793461, 0.0020574087, -0.017187148, 0.003134012, 0.010211548, -0.027503386, 0.005789865, -0.019696381, -0.0052995733, -0.033985868, 0.056921557, -0.019599086, -0.040183682, 0.0016540746, -0.026491439, 0.029323319, 0.049413312, 0.019847747, 0.042458843, -0.038076997, 0.011858057, 0.0013553303, 0.03299066, -0.010259058, -0.025810383, -0.0058815354, 0.032596588, -0.022073135, -0.03894575, 0.020571278, -0.04379627, -0.021096723, -0.026880937, -0.014137665, -0.018543813, 0.017554907, 0.01188783, 0.040434837, -0.07022045, 0.056117658, -0.031302743, 0.02294655, 0.03650467, 0.025224641, 0.026944023, 0.026252264, 0.03315599, 0.0062662256, -0.025260232, -0.014106132, 0.0033606584, 0.009688753, 0.010798271, 0.0352009, 0.008045656, 0.04851338, 0.029954622, -0.041815203, 0.0055620708, 0.038794704, -0.0040555354, -0.028799374, -0.08350948, -0.017966092, 0.023017397, -0.029144956, 0.07524998, -0.034210704, 0.012452582, -0.006996522, -0.016042622, -0.010385993, -0.016919857, -0.016072419, -0.023483265, 0.019060519, -0.053134866, -0.02821491, -0.03677282, -0.033726525, -0.053215615, -0.001302941, -0.010810248, 0.0034890196, -0.021394167, -0.009748438, -0.009935726, 0.0470175, 0.022325838, -0.008152671, 0.04288697, -5.7762384E-4, -0.070925675, 0.035916097, 0.02674344, -0.011334605, 0.032122623, 0.04407752, 0.09785047, 0.0138429925, 0.012177432, -0.033997852, 0.031827297, 0.022627298, -0.030245744, -0.018767672, -0.018684138, -0.050827574], text:"in SNpc particularly, and whether targeting LRRK2 would slow down the progression of PD. Is DA\nneuronal death due to LRRK2 cell-autonomous function in neurons or is it caused by cell non-\nautonomous function in microglia and astrocytes? Modeling tissue-, cell type-, or even organelle-\nspeciﬁc expression of LRRK2 mutants would provide insightful clues. Although challenges exist\nand questions remain, great developments have been achieved in the LRRK2 ﬁeld from the labo-\nratory bench to the clinic over the past two decades.\nAcknowledgments\nY.X. was supported by grants from the National Institutes of Health (NIH)/National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke\n(NINDS) R01 NS112506 and Parkinson's Foundation Stanley Fahn Junior Faculty award PF-JFA-1934. J.Y. was supported by\ngrants from the NIH National Institute of General Medical Sciences (NIGMS) R01 GM136904 and the National Science Founda-\ntion (NSF) 2115690. The authors apologize for not including all related references owing to space limitations.\nDeclaration of interests\nY.X. and J.Y. are the inventors of a non-provisional patent covering activators of LRRK2 mRNA decay and the use thereof to\ntreat Parkinson's disease or LRRK2-related diseases.\nReferences\n1. Zimprich, A. et al. (2004) Mutations in LRRK2 cause autosomal-\ndominant parkinsonism with pleomorphic pathology. Neuron\n44, 601–607\n2. Paisan-Ruiz, C. et al. (2004) Cloning of the gene containing mu-\ntations that cause PARK8-linked Parkinson's disease. Neuron\n44, 595–600\n3. Lees, A.J. et al. (2009) Parkinson's disease. Lancet 373, 2055–2066\n4. Mata, I.F. et al. (2006) LRRK2 in Parkinson's disease: protein\ndomains and functional insights. Trends Neurosci. 29, 286–293\n5. Alessi, D.R. and Pfeffer, S.R. (2024) Leucine-rich repeat kinases.\nAnnu. Rev. Biochem., Published online April 15, 2024. https://\ndoi.org/10.1146/annurev-biochem-030122-051144\n6. West, A.B. et al. (2007) Parkinson's disease-associated muta-", page:12}}, {_id:2550, properties:{chunk_index:1, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p12::1::3d9e0395", embedding:[-0.0070222947, 0.07279086, -0.1409879, 0.0036774334, 0.0600251, -0.05807339, 0.011545998, 0.042229168, 6.508578E-4, -0.0276599, -0.036209606, 0.08386353, 0.1051254, 0.011919748, -0.015765412, -0.043995455, 0.009669903, -0.027079912, -0.023160689, 0.059720997, -0.05953404, 0.0034543131, 0.008085648, -0.058605734, 0.027857915, 0.02972522, -0.0061062514, 0.0015832613, -0.01219467, 0.03475174, 0.08995971, -0.055692475, -0.042806674, -0.0339