.049608823, -0.0018066119, -0.044126738, 0.032489285, -0.01734883, 0.017378986, -0.013346101, 0.0046659047, 0.019426389, -0.03488248, -0.06376933, 0.04575427, 0.02588689, -0.046741806, 0.037782233, 0.09706822, 0.03542726, 0.007959573, 0.089595504, 0.0458181, -7.767146E-4, -0.03211731, -0.0012348267, -0.013714243, 0.043127056, -0.044455066, -0.034905702, -0.04437462, -0.009062675, 0.0058180178, 0.0037232286, -0.0070423093, -0.0034780554, -0.027517367, 0.001943991, -0.010700972, -0.014998682, -0.04200658, 0.0442179, 0.016110588, 0.0040382235, -0.012154795, -0.049172983, 0.0290381, 0.037943933, 0.03957198, -0.011138977, -0.008395463, 0.02653991, 0.027742162, 0.04217507, -0.013049912, -0.040406965, -0.010019877, 0.0016579645, 0.0015490963, -0.060172625, 0.031704288, -0.010540528, -0.018002804, -0.034313556, -0.013720214, -0.0033667695, 0.030337743, 0.0031284157, 0.008314054, -0.05454473, 0.05094169, -0.03442228, 0.0062266705, -0.008216202, 0.013337596, 0.0043114433, 0.039459657, 0.03129618, -0.00800576, -0.007878904, -0.040241282, -0.0237903, 0.029522972, 0.019320967, 0.0480283, -0.00217309, 0.04476829, 0.06090664, -0.060735527, 0.00875154, 0.049085975, -0.009779362, -0.024158001, -0.08690326, 0.02064708, -0.010924528, -0.039773837, 0.023947796, -0.0015256391, -0.02315419, 0.015396645, -0.019008124, -0.010774721, -0.024263917, -0.03316086, 0.0105789015, 0.041112233, -0.071790256, -0.006367645, -0.041044325, -0.022612376, -0.046683762, 0.0250086, -0.012397438, 0.010169987, -0.01523574, 0.02635087, -0.0015867678, 0.04222, 0.018588522, 0.016302697, 0.034538154, 0.016249247, -0.046112437, 0.032905154, 0.014140587, 0.011495216, -0.0040600887, 0.06443371, 0.10982598, 0.01723187, 0.01865529, -0.034512773, 0.011083315, 0.03793582, -0.024144195, -0.016376223, -0.020117497, -0.06680444], text:"Annu. Rev. Biochem., Published online April 15, 2024. https://\ndoi.org/10.1146/annurev-biochem-030122-051144\n6. West, A.B. et al. (2007) Parkinson's disease-associated muta-\ntions in LRRK2 link enhanced GTP-binding and kinase activities\nto neuronal toxicity. Hum. Mol. Genet. 16, 223–232\n7. Greggio, E. and Cookson, M.R. (2009) Leucine-rich repeat ki-\nnase 2 mutations and Parkinson's disease: three questions.\nASN Neuro 1, e00002\n8. Ross, O.A. et al. (2011) Association of LRRK2 exonic variants\nwith susceptibility to Parkinson's disease: a case-control\nstudy. Lancet Neurol. 10, 898–908\n9. Fava, V.M. et al. (2019) Pleiotropic effects for Parkin and LRRK2\nin leprosy type-1 reactions and Parkinson's disease. Proc. Natl.\nAcad. Sci. U. S. A. 116, 15616–15624\nTrends\nTrends in\nin Molecular\nMolecular Medicine\nMedicine\nFigure 5. Potential LRRK2 targeting strategies. LRRK2 can be targeted through multiple avenues. Signiﬁcant progress\nhas been made in targeting LRRK2 kinase activity and levels (in black). Several highly potent, brain-penetrant, and selective\ncompounds including GNE7915, GNE-0877 (also known as DNL201), PF-475, PF-360, MLi-2, and DNL151 (the closely\nresembled form of DNL201) have been developed. DNL151/BIIB122 is advancing to Phase 2b efﬁcacy studies in the LUMA\n(NCT05348785) trial. Efforts to target LRRK2 levels have also advanced using the LRRK2 antisense oligonucleotide (ASO)\ninhibitor BIIB094, which degrades LRRK2 mRNA, and this is currently in the Phase 1 study REASON (NCT03976349). AICAr,\nthe cell-permeable precursor of AICAR, targeting LRRK2 mRNA decay, and PROTACs, aiming for LRRK2 protein degradation,\nrepresent promising approaches. In addition, GTPase modulators, crucial cellular interactors of LRRK2, and inhibition of\nLRRK2 dimerization hold potential as therapeutics (in gray), even though they are not currently advancing to later stages.", page:12}}, {_id:2551, properties:{chunk_index:2, id:"PIIS1471491424001898.pdf::p12::2::cef3e8d1", embedding:[-0.044782754, 0.060656603, -0.13150938, -0.046011817, 0.06567023, -0.09161649, -0.011298767, -0.0016491169, -0.018187962, 0.0054186033, -0.0422996, 0.048946396, 0.08076