3, 0.03062707, -0.029862393, 0.031900752, -0.024215752, 0.039785318, 8.680837E-4, 0.007406873, 0.04428604, -0.0054587456, -0.015933847, 0.07057455, 0.036302775, -0.022901103, 0.0014091921, 0.0625164, 0.06688645, -0.00849625, -0.007769336, -0.035779487, 0.042410705, 3.5055007E-5, -0.052527014, -0.008107091, -0.019999227, -0.014952876], text:"synaptic terminals) and is involved in vesicle transport \nand \nneurotransmitter \nrelease.29 \nSmall \noligomeric \naggregates are also present in blood and cerebrospinal \nfluid.30 Lewy bodies represent the end stage of a cellular \nprocess, in which initial small α-synuclein aggregates are \nobserved in the cytoplasm of the neuron and then \ncoalesce into diffuse pale bodies. This coalescence is \nfollowed by the formation of an aggregation seed, which \nleads to diffuse synuclein aggregating into filaments. \nThese filaments then form a classic Lewy body (figure 1).31 \nLewy bodies might be detrimental to neurons in that they \nare space occupying lesions that might alter cellular \nfunction; however, most evidence supports the toxicity of \nsmall aggregates and oligomers in the pathogenesis of \nParkinson’s disease, rather than larger aggregates.32\nUsing α-synuclein staining to detect Lewy bodies in post-\nmortem donors with differing levels of Lewy body \npathology, Braak and colleagues proposed a staging of \nParkinson’s disease, in which the disease could start in the \nperiphery, in the gut, or in the olfactory system, and spread \nto subcortical and then cortical brain regions (figure 1).31 \nThe Braak hypothesis is supported by studies of the \nprodromal phases of Parkinson’s disease, including \nunbiased studies of primary health-care records, which \nshow that in the general population, people who develop \nFigure 1: α-Synuclein has a central role in the pathophysiology of Parkinson’s disease \nα-Synuclein aggegrates in oligomers and fibrils, and forms Lewy bodies found in the gut, brainstem, and cerebral \ncortex\nMonomers\nOligomers\nFibrils\nLewy body and\nLewy neurite formation\nCell dysfunction\nand loss\nFor more on the Global \nParkinson's Genetics Program \nsee gp2.org.", page:3}}, {_id:2749, properties:{chunk_index:0, id:"1-s2.0-S0140673623014782-main.pdf::p4::0::b645cb60", embedding:[0.069736384, 0.07821997, -0.17116012, -0.06438354, 0.0073323366, -0.0020620266, -0.024467992, 0.019810366, 0.048194844, -0.07403315, 0.04128384, 0.017980348, 0.09816966, 0.0034359526, -0.043047752, -0.031648133, -0.033580784, -0.043681737, -0.019873042, 0.012173743, -0.046850782, 0.02102028, -0.018567324, -0.024852179, 0.045733813, 0.08319928, -0.038130194, -0.02971268, 0.046567753, 0.017097386, 0.089643106, 0.0022832062, 0.0032058521, -0.030433508, -0.06299353, -0.044055153, 0.04290821, 0.007315541, 0.016179984, 0.046549954, -0.023892447, -0.035325594, -0.032947592, -0.08207012, -0.013301521, 0.029335316, 0.050437026, -0.001623185, 0.051978875, -0.024408383, 0.028457709, -0.018958643, -0.024706692, -0.03459509, 0.098277725, 0.01777218, 0.0052189096, -0.024276435, 0.029908227, -0.01639883, 0.06585211, 0.06366371, -0.024621645, 0.03201567, 0.021438574, -0.04027474, -0.02479152, 0.07634808, 0.0024918572, -0.04905728, 0.047516212, -0.005152067, 0.0069214487, -0.009115852, -0.039762016, 0.021798814, 0.022728585, -0.018996293, -0.030484878, 0.018050296, 0.023886094, 0.0021317718, 0.028243871, 0.019096866, 0.08512023, -0.0072302916, -0.05260064, 0.0022021353, 0.0041629807, 0.054126967, 0.024125686, 0.04786615, -0.007248132, 0.024420721, -0.036635637, -0.0045960792, -0.009950225, 0.011109498, -0.04784931, -0.040051106, -0.054200236, 0.0024006155, -0.009631111, 0.013389119, 0.034623615, 0.040775392, 0.014129303, -0.05016596, -0.010152618, 0.031154303, -0.039526694, 0.04649495, -0.006460685, -0.025632927, 0.0029656447, -0.044699203, 0.040556177, -0.0065442114, 0.021373665, 0.052948803, -0.01391874, -0.015383716, -0.0105283195, 0.05107686, -0.014316383, 0.031246431, -0.025337348, -0.042409487, 0.