248, 0.017119505, -0.040653605, -0.0073520946, 0.03335178, -0.06836194, 0.0031965927, -0.049093205, -0.030306842, -0.0055235866, 0.0017977604, 0.001315451, 0.029107787, -0.0016980583, 0.034826256, -0.0039898297, 0.05585513, 0.036529526, -0.016189558, 0.017491704, 0.0030597209, -0.011584927, -0.010596514, -0.028965605, -0.007498616, 0.03884112, 0.02793378, 0.01907061, 0.03775663, 0.016666623, 0.01712549, -0.003697388, -0.076243, -0.008584152, 0.035326056, 0.007852952, -0.036261406, -0.057977356, -0.015033165, 0.028140891, -0.01334785, 0.06149841, -0.04791539, -0.0085622, -0.018519383, -0.01592411, -0.006093677, -0.0211043, -0.016122673, 0.0016607086, 0.036158428, -0.0540149, -0.010854943, -0.09800503, -0.024734955, -0.051022742, 0.017714467, 0.019108385, -0.0181797, -0.024696836, 0.0011980479, -0.012736424, 0.05262109, 0.019087495, -0.019359596, 0.057875272, -0.0148219755, -0.036304742, 0.05150685, 0.014817743, -0.01146883, -0.0059183897, 0.024152946, 0.07978441, -0.029002313, 0.006481988, -0.006397747, 0.028190037, 0.007647198, -0.052198846, -0.04308494, -0.011155643, -0.016056126], text:"testing the loss-of-function synucleinopenia hypothesis by evaluating the clinical and neurodegenerative rescue \neffect of replenishing the levels of monomeric α-synuclein.   \n1. Introduction \nAlpha-synuclein, a ubiquitous protein string of 140 amino acids, has \nbeen conserved for hundreds of millions of years in virtually all species \nof the animal kingdom and expressed in most tissues of the human body \n[1]. Did evolutionary forces preserve this protein to ensure it would \nyield toxicity and cause disease to its host once transformed into insol­\nuble cross-β aggregates, the amyloid state known as Lewy bodies? \nMost reviews about α-synuclein in Parkinson’s disease (PD) gloss \nover its biological functions (such as regulating vesicular trafficking and \nneurotransmitter exocytosis [2]) to focus on the in vitro and animal \nmodel-based evidence for toxicity [3]. The idea of toxicity, never \ndemonstrated in humans, emerged after a reconstruction of longitudinal \nevents from cross-sectional autopsy data. The cross-β state into which \nα-synuclein folds is a very stable configuration. Once it loses its mono­\nmeric and soluble structure, α-synuclein ceases to function. However, \nthis loss of function has received little attention because knocking it out \nin young mice yields no adverse biological effect. \nFor the last two decades, research efforts have been guided by the \nprinciple that PD is caused by a gain of toxic function α-synuclein exerts \nin its aggregated, misfolded form, evident under the microscope as Lewy \nbodies and Lewy neurites –collectively referred to as Lewy pathology. As \nmost studies only quantify and interpret changes in the insoluble frac­\ntion of this peptide, a hypothesis based on only one side of the protein \nhomeostasis story has dominated thinking and contemporary research. \nAfter a short historical overview, we make the case that the aggre­\ngation of α-synuclein into Lewy pathology is a normal, protective reac­", page:1}}, {_id:2845, properties:{chunk_index:2, id:"1-s2.0-S1353802024000890-main.pdf::p1::2::326d002d", embedding:[0.09897583, 0.07631676, -0.14963223, -0.013091245, 0.040318422, -0.014066639, 0.005761124, 0.046468258, 0.02952356, 6.468158E-5, -0.014753962, 0.0018734077, 0.099753454, 0.024513049, 0.01898757, -0.014289352, -0.03453911, -0.029753588, -0.030115154, 0.0038832587, -0.08864336, -0.034875315, 0.03177021, 0.008323563, 0.059882108, 0.12551543, -0.052164864, -0.019278511, 0.0011604106, -0.010552921, 0.10726269, -0.04808357, -0.026413668, -0.026820004, -0.04403262, -0.038910426, 0.048461046, 0.031059323, 0.012447556, -0.0035744575, -0.012815772, 0.04139116, 0.008239224, -0.05864594, -0.010130214, 0.036729667, 0.04862231, -0.026476761, 0.055570923, -0.06521462, 0.024747647, 0.003700915, -0.027765993, -0.042451993, 0.10906849, -0.02558602, 0.036351472, -0.05676369, 0.028893817, -0.0