3832, 0.07385691, -0.027597565, 0.04996687, 0.007228628, 0.0015346158, 0.007857308, 0.029798599, 0.006999857, -0.016673986, -0.02454118, 0.022302227, -0.042270157, -0.006391218, -0.0025446657, -0.04625106, -0.04567715, -0.04866455, -0.045362294, -0.03082196, 0.010490025, -0.015911484, 0.016790835, -0.01883171, 0.049655344, 0.025325555, 0.004107182, -5.7892525E-4, -0.014438032, 3.065827E-4, 0.026157213, 0.038814392, -0.0042394255, 0.011062817, 0.007839664, 0.029372398, 0.014552739, 0.041706227, 0.040010605, 0.0313605, 0.043014366, 0.015670376, -0.08543885, -0.004905183, 0.04791792, 0.014713785, -0.032638308, -0.08051033, -0.020442894, 0.045057964, -0.0057082167, 0.0928455, -0.049091075, 0.017995536, -0.022264501, -0.020762319, 0.037054498, -0.037135843, -0.010727229, -0.015359259, 0.012325883, -0.06518946, -0.03351128, -0.040499672, -0.051324055, -0.036976308, 9.3378685E-4, 0.029976113, 0.036694046, -0.040218964, -0.026551776, -0.033704873, 0.03586453, -0.0035755294, 0.038418327, 0.023669101, 0.020945426, -0.05261039, 0.05529263, 0.0047964524, -0.009382508, 0.025636962, 0.042276546, 0.1007901, -0.0010677141, -0.004534338, -0.030100666, 0.06616095, 0.017083354, -0.06729636, 0.0036879075, -0.036116462, -0.020486481], text:"Parkinsonism and Related Disorders 122 (2024) 106077\n2\nα-synuclein was the key constituent of Lewy bodies [6], the ‘hallmark’ \n(implying cause) of PD, and that a point mutation in the 53rd amino acid \nof the SNCA gene was associated with an aggressive form of PD [7]. In \n2003, Braak and colleagues examined the distribution of Lewy pathol­\nogy in 41 brains of patients with PD and 69 of individuals with Lewy \npathology without a history of neurological disease. They organized the \nbrains from least to most α-synuclein staining and made static data \nsuccumb to dynamic pareidolia: Lewy pathology moved cephalad in six \nstages starting in the medulla oblongata, with parkinsonian motor fea­\ntures occurring once the spreading process reached the midbrain [8]. \nThe notion of “propagation” attributed to the independent distribution \nof pathology in unrelated brains and the subsequent observation that \nLewy bodies can appear in embryonic striatal transplantation tissue [9] \ngave birth to the “prion-like” idea about Lewy pathology [10]. Pathol­\nogy had become synonymous with pathogenesis. \nThere is a fundamental problem with the Braak staging and the hy­\npothesis of toxic gain of synuclein function: Lewy pathology in the brain \ndoes not correlate with parkinsonism, disease severity, or the degree of \nneurodegeneration (neuronal loss) (Fig. 1). It is now known that neither \nthe presence nor distribution of Lewy pathology predicts motor or \ncognitive symptoms [11], and that the Braak and Hoehn & Yahr stages \nbear no relationship to each other (including when directly examining \nthe data from Braak et al.) [12], that neurodegeneration and cellular \ndysfunction precede α-synuclein pathology in the substantia nigra [13], \nthat the proportion of neurons with Lewy pathology has nothing to do \nwith disease duration [14], and that, validating the pioneering obser­\nvations of Burke and colleagues, the more Lewy pathology in the nigra, \nthe more nigral neurons remain [14].", page:2}}, {_id:2847, properties:{chunk_index:1, id:"1-s2.0-S1353802024000890-main.pdf::p2::1::4f0f7336", embedding:[0.10766013, 0.08516902, -0.13260542, -0.050111532, 0.059390724, -0.027652709, 0.024636738, 0.029546978, 0.034363847, -0.014967192, -0.013386613, 0.015287308, 0.09960836, 0.021236109, 0.01779659, -0.06915518, -0.03877698, -0.015509422, -0.006968524, 0.066779114, -0.04311476, -0.021167766, 0.024921197, -0.012299631, 0.02101098, 0.09820657, -0.053209577, -0.052546397, 0.019432511, 0.020671684, 0.08774728, -0.03687724, -0.03235976, 0.023995176, -0.0015694755, -0.06879495, 0.071255445, 0.038902238, 0.053944334, -0.030882826, 0.016102614, 0.015618305, 0.019296318, -0.050049476, -8.189003E-4, 0.063426234, 0.037390064, -0.032373