469247, 0.033662435, -0.0023643023, -0.08469551, 0.037092324, 0.003986002, -0.031036401, 0.05213287, -0.029660597, 0.06293151, -0.012757478, -0.024908185, -0.04444145, -0.0065021245, 0.074507885, -0.07409405, 0.061205003, -0.04898972, 0.02079069, -0.03448504, 0.025069073, -0.015639218, 0.051773116, -0.012286383, -0.01356069, 0.024946097, 0.018380111, -0.027221667, 0.004543994, -0.014319723, -0.025257183, 0.03370427, 0.080744505, -0.011282828, 0.009063049, 0.0847545, 0.06675318, 0.006761696, -0.039765295, -0.033635244, 0.020876888, 0.035016287, -0.046448257, -0.010100931, -0.051848236, -0.0033784867, 0.03620623, -0.0102580115, -0.013798762, 0.0033916733, -0.035494387, 0.042214185, -0.04050396, -0.0012643599, -0.0077010184, 0.079559684, 0.0085163135, -0.02979307, -0.0034376804, 0.0057395073, 0.014296739, 0.07098733, -0.039120913, 0.035257854, -0.0044268663, -0.014973277, -0.014640565, 0.0074476255, -0.003358791, 0.0023815252, -0.020158198, -0.0059894775, -0.037923675, -0.04138935, 0.019068638, -0.033995442, -0.025005901, -0.023230324, -0.01565942, -0.027463775, -0.0030108907, 0.008731071, 0.013224535, -1.2723295E-4, 0.024971303, 0.012924201, 0.0334926, 0.0036151323, -0.021462385, -0.011538393, 0.012076396, 0.004176836, 0.013221816, -0.0041565057, 0.010996488, 0.048978772, 0.023414457, 0.029521564, 0.02812326, -0.0015008767, 0.017216187, 0.003956094, -0.07680438, 0.018588128, 0.044573296, 0.0020836962, -0.033513654, -0.08089967, -0.046023056, 0.074507535, 0.012825493, 0.091909446, -0.055582885, -0.015957644, -0.033673927, -0.022259267, 0.028860683, -0.020892845, -0.004662557, -0.024259338, 0.026920928, -0.041399594, -0.003928345, -0.0978491, -0.050906353, -0.032655843, 0.0019913744, -0.0021373492, 0.043225933, -0.048091352, -0.009918072, -0.033095345, 0.03426633, 0.035054013, 0.0026355379, 0.037294112, 0.0057032667, -0.04597364, 0.03867369, 0.0077494574, -0.014904623, 0.028528133, 0.026236042, 0.060700994, -0.04353971, 0.0067685107, -0.006355249, 0.025549415, -0.0016352924, -0.059380054, -0.019624893, -0.013180097, -0.032797705], text:"post-mortem by histopathological methods. It has been necessary to \n“embrace complexity” [17] to accept the idea that a depleted natural \npeptide can become toxic and reconcile the paradox that higher levels of \nα-synuclein, not lower, are associated with preservation of brain volume \n[18]. \nSince proteins such as α-synuclein and Aβ42 are ubiquitous in the \nanimal kingdom, the odds are their functions are critical for survival, not \nfor natural anti-selection [19]. Even the phosphorylation of α-synuclein, \nlong thought to be a part of the pathophysiology of PD, has been recently \nfound to be necessary for its normal function in the regulation of \nneuronal communication by calibrating synaptic activity [20]. \n2. Proteinopathy mythology \n2.1. Myth 1. SNCA multiplication overexpresses α-synuclein: ergo it must \nbe toxic \nThe discovery that SNCA duplication and triplication overexpress \nα-synuclein led to the conclusion that PD resulted from a “dosage” effect \nFig. 1. Braak Staging: Proposed vs Actual Data. Braak and colleagues made static α-synuclein-staining data from 110 unrelated brains appear dynamic: Lewy \npathology was envisioned as “spreading” cephalad in six stages. The predictions that pathology staging increases with age and correlates with clinical staging proved \nfalse –with the same data. \nA.J. Espay and A.J. Lees", page:2}}, {_id:2851, properties:{chunk_index:0, id:"1-s2.0-S1353802024000890-main.pdf::p3::0::63a9ca80", embedding:[0.04606582, 0.06266639, -0.14619088, -0.030107427, 0.03770362, 0.01171554, 0.0038573302, 0.04779628, 0.012303441, -0.020471703, -0.022722136, 5.696204E-4, 0.109378085, 0.03530462, 0.015956266, -0.032716796, -0.0188316, -0.05152492, -0.04224808, 0.04318838, -0.053843617, -0.02350511, 0.03154797, -0.04400136, 0.08618788, 0.09430209, -0.054523256, -0.026820872, 0.012661133, 0.017793017, 0.107454024, -0.01586613, -0.010674087, 0.004875536, -0.04704