24, 0.015716897, -0.040891603, 0.033897776, -0.0037404122, 0.009816595, 0.009799537, 0.01685294, -0.030794008, 0.016795756, 0.00687916, -0.046649523, 0.018901603, 0.079903126, 0.007909278, -0.0047474476, 0.10061653, 0.057918955, 7.270271E-4, -0.050829347, -0.012552353, 0.007851574, 0.040551066, -0.058919214, -0.035334177, -0.03614955, -0.021119695, 0.021242345, -0.031770814, -0.0056295525, 0.025769025, -0.02292256, 0.030726645, -0.019614864, -0.021345979, -0.02559633, 0.061039574, -0.01632839, -0.042570896, -0.02003764, -0.031911805, 0.02384169, 0.055008516, -0.02541731, 0.042508192, 5.5374716E-5, 0.008678058, -0.017831534, 0.042231746, 0.02617768, -0.013206972, 0.008456746, 0.020958649, -0.048227552, 0.010841543, 0.017036047, -0.04178888, -0.020094035, -0.034099523, -0.029716074, -0.03158743, 0.008786697, -1.6896584E-4, 0.0499297, -0.024424806, 0.054457158, 0.0090599675, 0.025074983, 0.0066860085, -0.02918065, -0.011785545, 0.039632283, 0.022070399, 0.020094465, -0.0034300687, -0.023800448, 0.033364367, 0.03178, 0.0045861984, 0.02217737, 0.027037457, 0.053182535, 0.029449804, -0.0680773, -0.012246346, 0.043354355, 0.034495253, -0.03474923, -0.0721111, -0.04610507, 0.034045964, -0.018520696, 0.06729176, -0.056550864, 0.009678472, -0.0070722615, -0.025867919, 0.011608637, -0.061233263, -0.0034339472, -0.0061385725, 0.024667049, -0.04177363, -0.021880317, -0.08680314, -0.04177905, -0.067945115, 0.0122412415, 0.016781142, 0.034395672, -0.046669107, 0.019615045, -0.031803552, 0.03704019, 0.00665424, 0.026290389, 0.021870801, 0.027246378, -0.025322707, 0.052764617, 0.010025458, -0.020249674, 0.026365869, 0.032189574, 0.07301132, -0.021554323, 0.0098528, -0.03305676, 0.027327282, 0.02014607, -0.06309371, -0.0076513705, -0.04777442, -0.035375215], text:"Parkinsonism and Related Disorders 122 (2024) 106077\n3\nof α-synuclein: the higher the protein level, the more malignant the \nphenotype [21]. The overexpression of a protein makes it more likely to \naggregate through the physical phenomenon of homogeneous nucle­\nation. However, the longer the aggregation process goes on, the lower \nthe normal protein levels become. Patients with SNCA duplication have \nvery low levels of α-synuclein in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) [22]. On \nthe assumption that the genetic overexpression of α-synuclein implies a \ntoxic dose effect, in an observational study of nearly 1,100 PD cases, \nMarkopoulou and colleagues tested the hypothesis that REP1 genotypes, \nwhich increases the risk of PD via increased SNCA expression, are \nassociated with worse motor and cognitive function [23]. “Paradoxi­\ncally,” high SNCA expression was associated with better motor (HR =\n0.85) and cognitive outcomes (HR = 0.85) than cases with low SNCA \nexpression [23]. Furthermore, the lymphoblastoid cell lines derived \nfrom a parkinsonian kindred with SNCA duplication, shown to have \nincreased expression of SNCA mRNA, were “surprisingly” more resistant \nthan control lines to various insults, including dexamethasone, 3-meth­\nyladenine, and rotenone [24]. It has also been reported that SNCA \nmultiplication size is not associated with the onset of motor or cognitive \nsymptoms [25] and the SNCA penetrance can be as low as 30% [26,27]. \n2.2. Myth 2. Knocking down α-synuclein is inconsequential \nMost studies testing the behavioral and anatomical changes of \nknocking α-synuclein out of young mice have reported no changes in \nbehavior or in cell count and concluded that the loss of α-synuclein is \ninconsequential. The output is different, however, when aging, the most \nimportant risk factor for PD, is incorporated into the models. Upon \nknocking down α-synuclein in aged rats [28] or aged non-human pri­\nmates [29], nigrostriatal degeneration and behavioral changes are", page:3}}, {_id:2852, properties:{chunk_index:1, id:"1-s2.0-S1353802024000890-main.pdf::p3::1::85dd8f0e", embedding:[0.045783512, 0.036808603, -0.16786037, -0.049317583, 8.566004E-4, 0.018710323, -0.01