-0.010899416, 0.011512526, -0.021180823, -0.013888311, 0.026737714, 0.01814409, 0.034211777, 0.026843619, -0.006603282, -0.037334085, -0.07253487, -0.02135424, 0.03895537, 6.2525505E-6, -0.037254095, -0.059263464, -0.04201725, 0.040698696, -0.02409992, 0.081357956, -0.054222766, 0.009513257, -0.028072925, -0.043713756, 0.0065579955, -0.017861817, -0.0066891853, -0.0148694245, 0.03524499, -0.03197237, -0.019343983, -0.085128255, -0.0029152168, -0.038932502, 0.012167674, 0.002765813, 0.007163729, -0.038955983, -0.0029672028, -0.03639588, 0.0779628, -0.018101895, -0.0060506007, 2.3786021E-4, 0.008316469, 0.0026101524, 0.038635485, 0.034349285, -0.036001094, 0.007108642, 0.045330856, 0.094101675, -0.0029046813, -0.025894614, -0.028065903, 0.036363836, -0.00128112, -0.07191082, 0.0018962853, -0.018674698, -0.0070447475], text:"With pathology having a dubious association with degeneration or \nsymptoms and normal monomers incapable of causing disease, a ‘gain of \ntoxic function’ paradigm required postulating that oligomers, the low \nand medium molecular weight aggregates of α-synuclein, were the \nculprit. Under supersaturated conditions, which are necessary for the \nformation of amyloid, oligomers are ephemeral (their half-lives \nmeasured in hours) and usually dissociate back to monomers rather \nthan proceeding to form fibers [39]. A key weakness of the “toxic olig­\nomers” idea is that oligomers depend on a diminishing pool of soluble \nmonomers for their formation. The studies that find no evidence of \ntoxicity for any oligomer species in cell models receive little attention \n[40] or are framed ambiguously (e.g., “Dual and Opposing Effects”) \n[41]. A pivotal publication that drove large investments in anti-Aβ \noligomeric treatments in the field of Alzheimer’s disease, published in \nNature in 2006 [42], was found by a Science investigation in July 2002 \nto have been fabricated [43]. As a measure of its enormous influence, as \nof January 7, 2024, it has been referenced 2,327 times. \nFig. 2. The Myth of Classifying Diseases According to the Shapes of Fibrils. \nAs in other forms of pareidolia, pathology distribution is conceived as if \n“spreading” from one region to another, `a la Braak. Since the nucleation \nmechanism governing the water-to-ice transformation (as in the generation of \nsnowflakes) is similar to that for the monomer-to-amyloid transformation of \nproteins, the spread of pathology is passive, not active, and stochastic, not \npredictable or deterministic. Just as the architecture of snowflakes under ul­\ntrastructural microscopy cannot be used to determine where they came from, \nneither can neurodegenerative diseases be understood or classified according to \nthe shapes of the fibrils found at autopsy. (D = disease). \nA.J. Espay and A.J. Lees", page:3}}, {_id:2860, properties:{chunk_index:0, id:"1-s2.0-S1353802024000890-main.pdf::p4::0::2b5c246a", embedding:[0.07481787, 0.079144575, -0.16851136, -0.07146311, 0.03580961, -0.0548631, 0.0061671706, 0.05428574, 0.018893145, -0.032560155, -0.016772414, 0.038891967, 0.06488803, 0.019838741, -0.030583961, -0.051191226, 5.269044E-4, -0.10251967, -0.059399933, 0.011067162, -0.038254797, -0.021601565, -0.009040539, -0.001421357, 0.06636798, 0.06502826, -0.059006523, 0.009153983, 0.006482547, -0.01249309, 0.06753766, -0.04681694, -0.02802323, -0.0061573065, -0.05604478, -0.02387667, 0.053585224, 0.006692858, 0.0126509825, -0.0030157927, 0.0073869377, 0.010992817, 0.05168023, -0.057316225, -0.0137383025, 0.089405574, 0.031062922, 0.0063732304, 0.102927156, -0.07682065, 0.0035103734, 0.019912865, 0.017580066, -0.034066092, 0.09064748, 0.06823579, -0.014439337, -0.015510052, 0.03759115, -0.0025443118, 0.07816143, 0.10048143, -0.04912808, 0.014561713, 0.07447215, -0.052493937, 0.0030629246, 0.046626586, 0.012140786, -0.037446517, 0.037814632, -0.03650413, 0.0013205868, 0.04248734, -0.0147498865, -0.02248737, 0.01672858, -0.0011165314, -0.039908804, 0.01777825, 0.04