04947978, 0.006057234, -0.033136435, -0.04763585, 0.023017153, 0.034134533, -0.039673485, -0.023527946, -0.038998786, -8.5507584E-4, 0.053029623, -0.033171803, -0.04741984, -0.004111394, -0.03197134, 0.019072285, -0.023154328, -0.0035186827, -0.04062974, 0.051615495, -0.0111006, -0.017429233, -0.01475223, -0.017706776, 0.031493686, 0.06628536, -0.03712364, 0.06232323, -0.022597317, 0.0044060294, 0.01688479, 0.005162345, -0.0042748633, -0.0059139756, -0.0028925487, 0.0011526028, -0.03188891, -0.04819806, 0.01840057, -0.025244718, 0.0037797904, -0.0032471481, -0.04351362, -0.041388124, 0.014495049, -0.011408881, 0.028785614, -0.0066606915, 0.016778845, -0.022384128, 0.043893643, 0.021127902, -0.009080221, -0.0045678215, -0.0074980306, 0.0060669747, -0.029480644, 0.0105734775, 0.003036032, 0.02779932, 0.028818293, 0.03455385, 0.033945568, -0.005490837, 0.009238136, -0.0045106392, -0.08306762, -0.0017191155, 0.04088428, 0.0035597042, -0.040291373, -0.09508146, -0.01680491, 0.06352848, -0.0064666984, 0.106773645, -0.041502632, 0.0045539243, -0.042225312, -0.01383774, 0.02053499, -0.024844922, 0.0058741276, -0.01117164, 0.03970644, -0.04704554, -0.020176332, -0.091796234, -0.016236676, -0.029379843, 0.009267245, -0.004921083, 0.03582359, -0.024734706, -0.008135932, -0.027513305, 0.049045607, 0.030277837, -0.0062287836, 0.024783682, 0.026071802, -0.04161497, 0.036154836, -0.009996421, -0.031073123, 0.008614136, 0.042250756, 0.08328586, -0.004416547, 0.0068814903, -0.021085327, 0.030225819, -0.0025222495, -0.056854498, -0.018531991, -0.020328073, -0.029311746], text:"used to assess the severity or progression of disease [44], monitor \nresponse to treatments, or biologically subtype patients for future neu­\nroprotective interventions. \n3. Proteins are victims, not villains \nAt a time when the only research tool available in neuropathology \nwas the search for clues on brain tissue with a microscope, no one could \nhave been faulted for assuming that whatever looked abnormal was the \nsource of the problem, not its consequence. Most neurologists still use \nthe word pathology as interchangeable with pathogenesis. Yet brain pa­\nthology is more commonly found in people without a history of neuro­\nlogical symptoms. The most recent blinded review of 1,647 autopsied \nindividuals is a case in point: up to seven different pathologies occur in \n161 combinations, with a match between pathology and diagnosis of \nonly between 19% and 45% [46]. Pathology is the messenger of a nor­\nmally reactive brain and is not specific to any one human neurodegen­\nerative disease. \nPutting the above section into context, let’s clarify the following \nabout proteins in general and α-synuclein in particular, highlighting key \nfeatures of the proteinopenia hypothesis in stark contrast with the pre­\nvailing proteinopathy hypothesis (Table 1). \n1. Proteins do not “accumulate”, they phase transform. Pathology \ndoes not increase in absolute terms; their increase is only relative to \nthe level of soluble monomers from which they come. The “spread” \nof pathology is passive (precipitation), not active (replication). \n2. Pathology is one end of protein homeostasis; normal protein is \nthe other. Pathology is made of what once were normal monomeric \nproteins, no longer in their native, soluble configuration. To our \nFig. 3. Seeding as One of Three Nucleation Mechanisms. Under supersaturated conditions, any protein can be triggered to precipitate by nucleation into amyloids", page:4}}, {_id:2862, properties:{chunk_index:2, id:"1-s2.0-S1353802024000890-main.pdf::p4::2::95b6d13d", embedding:[0.095229544, 0.07557709, -0.1593951, -0.034876663, 0.018087616, 0.0232242, -0.02686662, 0.034333088, 0.037695143, -0.032924514, -0.031727504, 0.037199497, 0.109355345, 0.007878249, -0.033351406, -0.026408227, 0.012546168, -0.07167117, -0.017430471, 0.08259189, -0.059628077, -0.016884796, 0.020038225, -0.024597619, 0.04995062, 0.06202568, -0.039578386, -0.033864345, -0.0