n be triggered to precipitate by nucleation into amyloids \nby either a catalyst, such as a virus or a nanoparticle (heterogeneous nucleation), via overexpression of a peptide (homogenous nucleation; e.g., SNCA mutations) or \nby adding a preformed nucleus (seeding; e.g., prion diseases). The formation of amyloid is dependent on the recipient conditions, not on the particular type of \nproteins or their amino acid sequence. Adding seeds to a tissue where proteins are in a non-supersaturated condition will not result in amyloid formation, protein \nunfolding, or any kind of templating. Modified with permission from Ezzat et al. Biology 2022, 11, 535. https://doi.org/10.3390/biology11040535. \nTable 1 \nContrasting the ‘synucleinopathy’ and ‘synucleinopenia’ hypotheses.   \nSynucleinopathy \nSynucleinopenia \nAlpha-synuclein \nCause of disease \nAffected by disease \nPathogenesis \nAccumulation of pathology \nDepletion of normal \nsynuclein \nLewy pathology \nToxic causal agent \nInert physical consequence \nConformation \nStrains (identical copies) \nPolymorphs (infinitely \ndiverse) \nPathology spread \nActive, Replication \nPassive, Nucleation \nTreatment \napproach \nClearance of Lewy \npathology \nRestoration of normal \nsynuclein  \nA.J. Espay and A.J. Lees", page:4}}, {_id:2863, properties:{chunk_index:0, id:"1-s2.0-S1353802024000890-main.pdf::p5::0::d7b79d78", embedding:[0.08331073, 0.106726974, -0.13457699, -0.036390644, 0.06469819, -0.008296016, 0.007329423, 0.05709661, 0.05411181, -0.028415738, -0.025288034, -4.4139245E-4, 0.115553185, 0.01453252, 0.025367446, -0.036783766, -0.04077275, -0.048415616, -0.019718196, 0.02086534, -0.06270453, -0.017339975, 0.05599077, -0.018007908, 0.040443238, 0.10514237, -0.057620194, -0.024662659, 0.0026307756, -0.02202216, 0.10518689, -0.041700117, -0.0034658068, -0.031897172, -0.033120025, -0.07079745, 0.049147196, 0.025105145, 0.015630754, 0.015107581, -0.0067831473, 0.06685696, 0.03873051, -0.032219388, 0.011384537, 0.08