9, -0.0107723195, -3.9331676E-4, 0.053214137, 0.006137592, 0.013110453, 0.08134432, 0.06876771, -0.008191985, -0.03677265, -0.02551383, 0.022051895, 0.037412904, -0.05778522, -0.01427783, -0.021956373, -0.02386469, 0.03207763, 0.00575063, -0.023172118, -0.013332363, -0.018245317, 0.034485944, -0.022273807, -0.0033742017, -0.059179544, 0.031776045, -0.0071560326, -0.03162794, -0.051264342, 0.01390568, 0.04144124, 0.049203698, -0.03768302, 0.05924783, -0.0078989845, 0.02016988, 0.014265882, 0.028392341, 0.024160538, -0.032654244, 7.0557423E-4, -0.0036518793, -0.024928918, -0.03178569, 0.0069925007, -0.056696407, -0.0110567035, -0.04404593, -0.029196473, -0.01902927, 0.022132691, -0.00154582, -0.005168379, -0.03767488, 0.00917934, -0.006932421, 0.0118216295, 0.020909762, -0.03585903, 0.014021917, 0.0060097952, -0.017637344, -0.0061302367, -0.028650401, -0.042785283, -0.013913929, -0.008416762, 0.018558545, 0.029471051, 0.038020167, 0.015599281, -0.039990403, -0.079138525, -0.013726946, 0.049274128, -0.012095315, -0.048132986, -0.072329104, -0.056323815, 0.060918964, -0.01385928, 0.07284556, -0.06529324, -0.020249693, -0.026471661, -0.030466165, 0.007011072, -0.03453863, -0.011156071, -0.014200089, 0.02488807, -0.0044449824, -0.032737248, -0.08580983, -0.03731511, -0.04071413, 0.008355244, 0.011745321, 0.008277541, -0.05434442, 0.0031688926, -0.0338346, 0.07213641, -0.0034296347, -0.033760857, 0.006809183, 0.024373433, -0.03474475, 0.020269286, 0.0018952045, 9.761634E-4, -0.0017582342, 0.03859583, 0.10640421, -0.0025646375, -0.013683157, -0.06212746, 0.048279043, 0.027735574, -0.04010031, -0.01917428, -0.008057547, -0.034533184], text:"Parkinsonism and Related Disorders 122 (2024) 106077\n5\nknowledge, only one study (Australian Network of Brain Banks \nstudy, n = 33 PD; 13 controls) has quantified the soluble fraction of \nα-synuclein, demonstrating that its levels get progressively lower as \nLewy pathology increases [47]. As most clinicopathologic studies \nhave focused on the pathology end, the other end of the protein \nhomeostasis, monomeric α-synuclein, has remained invisible. \n3. Protein aggregation generates polymorphs, not strains. Aggre­\ngation is a descriptor for a physical process of precipitation in which \nsoluble monomers phase transform into insoluble amyloid in an \nirreversible process of nucleation regulated by the second law of \nthermodynamics and Gibbs free energy. The aggregation process and \nthe particular morphology of the aggregated protein or “seed” \ndepend entirely on the milieu, that is, the pH, temperature, con­\ncentration, and catalysts –the brain microenvironment. The \nmorphology of the resulting fibers is not encoded in the protein \nstructure itself [37]. No “strain” nor conformational template is \nnecessary. Any ultrastructural changes in the shape of the fibers, as \nrecently demonstrated for tau amyloid structures, result from \nexternal factors, such as inorganic salts and shaking conditions [48]. \nUsing the shapes of fibrils via ultrastructural microscopy to classify \nneurodegenerative \ndiseases \nonly \nprovides \nthe \nillusion \nof \nunderstanding. \n4. Therapeutic implications \nIt is often claimed that research into Alzheimer’s disease is ahead of \nParkinson’s and that it provides a lodestone to follow. After two decades \nand over 40 phase 2 or 3 anti-amyloid trials, slowing of cognitive decline \nhas now been demonstrated statistically, however marginally, with \nlecanemab [49] and donanemab [50]. Are these anti-Aβ monoclonal \nantibodies telling us something that the prior sixteen antibodies that \nsignificantly lowered brain amyloid couldn’t? It turns out that, through", page:5}}, {_id:2864, properties:{chunk_index:1, id:"1-s2.0-S1353802024000890-main.pdf::p5::1::9372ec5e", embedding:[0.08210093, 0.10325759, -0.12575021, -0.022629287, 0.072276875, -0.0017768312, 0.007713727, 0.06307543, 0.030084077, -0.012725738, -0.0334657, 0.035871588, 0.12423331, -0.018633895, 0.031037