ollier, J.W. Lipton, F.P. Manfredsson, Is \nalpha-synuclein loss-of-function a contributor to parkinsonian pathology? \nEvidence from non-human primates, Front. Neurosci. 10 (2016) 12. \n[30] M.J. Benskey, R.C. Sellnow, I.M. Sandoval, C.E. Sortwell, J.W. Lipton, F. \nP. Manfredsson, Silencing alpha synuclein in mature nigral neurons results in rapid \nneuroinflammation and subsequent toxicity, Front. Mol. Neurosci. 11 (2018) 36. \nFig. 4. Testing the Synucleinopenia Hypothesis: Rescue Medicine. Once below a certain threshold of compensation, the depletion of the soluble, normal fraction \nof α-synuclein compromises its function, and Parkinson’s symptoms become apparent. While Precision Medicine requires matching a molecular therapy to the mo­\nlecular biology of the recipient, still elusive in neurodegenerative research, Rescue Medicine allows “lumping” –correcting the universal proteinopenia of Parkin­\nson’s disease. \nA.J. Espay and A.J. Lees", page:6}}, {_id:2884, properties:{chunk_index:0, id:"1-s2.0-S1353802024000890-main.pdf::p7::0::eea0cce3", embedding:[0.015229333, 0.058048118, -0.15741397, -0.031591967, 0.04925369, -0.02798765, -0.017248074, 0.01851601, 0.04197625, -0.011127383, -0.024910374, 0.054227356, 0.090730086, 0.041703727, -0.0034365803, -0.039263587, -0.07607312, -0.043234672, -0.018238412, 0.0037965537, -0.0421935, -0.012527235, 0.062345903, -0.038789187, 0.050780814, 0.083977655, -0.034657177, -0.033633914, 0.020602912, 0.006403896, 0.11565289, -0.034518115, -0.02249023, -0.007888035, -0.0424324, -0.018823659, 0.055623967, 0.025149519, 0.015566597, 0.009242417, -0.0036741549, 0.06795454, 0.050043453, -0.043715592, 0.012475785, 0.06846485, 0.04627038, -0.034704734, 0.09289855, -0.10903653, 0.045549665, -0.01653388, 0.01502194, -0.032201782, 0.098982446, 0.014011987, -0.025571024, -0.027672147, 0.037770007, 0.0065713804, 0.038513638, 0.103150845, -0.022581296, 0.012513617, 0.049607325, -0.034327827, -0.016341463, 0.04375969, 0.02170612, -0.0593112